<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges Iran Not to Retaliate Against Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- France today urged Iran not to
retaliate against Germany, one day after a German court accused
Tehran of masterminding the assassination of three Iranian Kurds
and their interpreter in Berlin in September 1992.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said, "In
the immediate future, France is particularly attentive to the
arrangements Iran will make to prevent any inappropriate reaction
toward the citizens or the interests of Germany and, in a general
way, of Europe."
</P>
<P>
"The solidarity of France with Germany is complete in this
affair," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
A court in Berlin sentenced an Iranian grocer and a Lebanese
accomplice to life in prison for their role in killing the Kurds
in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin, and Germany recalled its
ambassador from Tehran after the ruling, an action which was
echoed by all the European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, the Iranian government has expelled four German
diplomats and recalled its own ambassador from Bonn, while about
800 Iranians staged a demonstration today in front of the German
embassy in Tehran to protest the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
On the perspective of economic damage Iran can bring to France,
the spokesman said, "The risk for France is not an economic or
trade risk. France is a trade partner of second importance for
Iran."
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, France imported a little more than 6 billion francs
(1.2 billion U.S. dollars) from Iran, with the petroleum
representing more than 95 percent of these imports," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that France's export to Iran falls well behind those by
the United States, Germany, Italy and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also reaffirmed France's opposition to a proposal
by the United States to impose an economic embargo upon Iran,
saying that embargo does not appear to be a proper way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
