<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Slow to 0.2 Percent Gain in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. retail sales slowed to an
increase of 0.2 percent in March, the smallest gain in four
months, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that sales totaled a seasonally adjusted
215.6 billion dollars, up slightly from 215.1 billion in February.
It was the smallest increase since a 0.1 percent drop last
November.
</P>
<P>
The report also revised the gain of sales in February up to 1.5
percent from the initial estimate of 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that sales of durable goods, items expected to last for
more than three years, edged up 0.1 percent after roaring ahead
3.1 percent in February. It was the smallest advance since a 0.3
percent decline in November.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales, which posted a 3.3 percent increase in February,
dropped by 0.6 percent, the first loss since a 0.9 percent decline
in November.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods such as food and fuel were up by 0.3
percent, also the smallest since a 0.1 percent gain in November.
The nondurable category posted a 0.4 percent gain in February.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in the U.S. represent about one-third of the
economic activity. Consumer spending has been a major driving
force for the strong U.S. economic expansion in recent months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
