<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Down for 3rd Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. producer prices declined
for the third month in a row mainly resulting from the largest
decline in energy costs in six years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department reported today that prices paid to
producers such as farms and factories fell by 0.1 percent last
month, following drops of 0.4 percent in February and 0.3 percent
in January.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the Producer Price Index (PPI) in
the U.S. recorded three consecutive declines since 1993.
</P>
<P>
But the report said the closely-watched core prices -- outside
food and energy -- shot up unexpectedly by 0.4 percent in March,
the largest in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
In March, the wholesale cost of energy fell by 3.4 percent, the
largest decline since March 1991.
</P>
<P>
Food prices rose by 0.9 percent, the first increase since
October. Among them, beef price jumped 6.8 percent, fish rose 7.9
percent and vegetables increased by 13.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices at the finished level outside food and energy were
propelled by a 2.5 percent increase in tobacco, the largest since
May, and rises in civilian aircraft, books, prescription drugs and
alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
Energy declines also helped push down indexes for prices at
earlier stages of the production process. Intermediate goods fell
by 0.6 percent and crude goods declined by 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The PPI measures the cost of goods before they reach consumers.
Its movement offers important clues for the future behavior of the
Consumer Price Index, which tracks the prices of services and
retail goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
