<HEADLINE> New Analysis: Cost Another Hurdle to NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The question of cost for NATO's
eastward expansion seems to have been neglected because so much
time has been devoted to discussing the "who and when" factors of
the move.
</P>
<P>
However, cost looms large as the final decision on which
countries should be taken in draw near.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled Madrid NATO summit in July is expected to decide
on new members for the 16-country bloc.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Russia's firm opposition to the enlargement plan,
the huge cost of the project is viewed by some experts as another
hurdle that the alliance can hardly leap over.
</P>
<P>
Studies by the Pentagon and independent United States think
tanks show the cost could be astronomical.
</P>
<P>
The Congressional Budget Office of the United States estimated
the cost of the planned expansion to be as high as 61 to 125
billion U.S. dollars, through to the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The Rand Corporation, a California-based think tank, came up
with a modest estimate of 14 to 110 billion dollars over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
The White House, which is firm and eager on pushing forward the
expansion process, predicted in February that it might cost
between 27 and 35 billion dollars to take in Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic, which are most likely to be the first
countries to join the alliance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
What will be the amount of money is not important. The real
question is where it will come from.
</P>
<P>
First, there is not even slightest chance of increases in
defense budgets of major NATO members. On the contrary, defense
spending is declining among member states.
</P>
<P>
The organization's major European allies are cutting their
armed forces as they try hard to meet European Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU) criteria.
</P>
<P>
The EMU, which hopes to launch a single European currency by
the year 1999, has established a budget deficit ceiling of three
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Extra funds for NATO expansion are hardly an option in view for
these countries.
</P>
<P>
Alliance budgets, such as the common infrastructure program,
known as the Security Investment Program, are already modest in
scale and are earmarked for agreed on measures.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, it seems to be paradoxical for new NATO members to
spend more money on their armed forces at a time when economic
revival and social reform need all the financial resources they
can get.
</P>
<P>
The annual defense budget of the Czech Republic is just 1.1
billion dollars, while Hungary has only 600 million dollars to
spend each year on its entire defense needs.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, money has traditionally been a major obstacle for new
NATO initiatives.
</P>
<P>
How to share the heavy burden of the expansion cost will become
a major controversy among the 16 NATO members once the enlargement
process is formally begun at the Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
"There's going to be a big fight within the alliance over who
will pay what. They haven't even warmed up for that one yet," a
NATO official warned.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's eastward expansion, which has already met strong
opposition from Russia since it tries to take in Central and
Eastern European countries, allies of the Soviet Union in the Cold
War era, is not likely to be a smooth process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
