<HEADLINE> US Chrysler Auto Workers Strike Shuts 4 Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A strike by 1,800 engine-plant
workers forced the U.S. No. 3 automaker Chrysler Corp. to shut
down its four profitable light-truck plants, according to reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The workers' strike kicked off at midnight Wednesday at the
Mound Road Engine Plant that is the sole supplier of engines for
some of the automaker's pickup trucks following failed
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Main issues in bargaining for a new local contract included
health and safety, discrimination against minority employees and
Chrysler's shifting of some engine component production to outside
suppliers, noted a strike leader.
</P>
<P>
The plant is the sole provider of V-6 and V-8 engines for Ram
and Dakota pickup trucks built at the Dodge City assembly complex
in nearby Warren. It is the primary source of engines for Ram
pickups assembled at St. Louis, although that plant uses some
engines made in Toluca, Mexico, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
The plant also is the only source of V-8 engines used in
Chrysler's popular Jeep Grand Cherokee sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The Mound Road plant also builds V-10 engines used in the
limited-production Dodge Viper and some Ram pickups.
</P>
<P>
The strike is expected to cost Chrysler as much as 11 million
U.S. dollars a day in net income, estimated an industrial analyst.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the company and representatives of the
United Auto Workers began in early January. The engine plant was
the last of Chrysler's U.S. manufacturing facilities where a local
contract had not been reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
