<HEADLINE> S. African Mining Companies Concerned About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- South African mining
companies have been closely watching the domestic situation in
Zaire, one of Africa's mining powers, after rebels seized
Lubumbashi, capital of the cooper-rich province of Shaba.
</P>
<P>
Southern African Broadcasting Association quoted informed
sources as saying today that at least three South African mining
companies have submitted tenders to develop Zairean copper mines.
</P>
<P>
De Beers, South Africa's diamonds giant, said it had five
diamond buying offices in Zaire and a contract with a Zairean
mining company to buy its products.
</P>
<P>
Lubumbashi fell to the rebels on Wednesday after stiff
resistance by the elite Presidential Security Division.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Laurent Kabila has announced a three-day truce to
allow President Mobutu Sese Seko to surrender power, warning that
his troops would resume fighting if the ailing Zairean leader did
not take the offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
