<HEADLINE> British Small Businessmen Support Labor Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 leaders of Britain's
small companies have voiced their support for Tony Blair's Labor
party, claiming that the ruling Conservative party has failed to
support them in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In a letter in The Times newspaper today, the industrialists
argued that there have been 11 tax increases and red tape had
expanded rather than contracted under the Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
"A small business has gone bust every three minutes of every
working day since 1992. (John) Major's belated announcement
earlier this week on business rates will do too little to make up
for what we have lost," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that small business can look forward with
confidence to a profitable future with a Labor government," it
added.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the open letter of these small
business people was another blow to the embattled Conservative
party, which has claimed to be the party of small business.
</P>
<P>
In a business manifesto due to be launched later today, the
Labor party, which is leading the Conservatives by some 20
percentage points in opinion polls, would unveil plans to get more
private funding into public projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
