<HEADLINE> UK Interest Rates Left Unchanged Before Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain's official interest rates
were left unchanged at the current 6 percent today and there will
be no interest rate rise before the general election on May 1, the
Bank of England said in a statement today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's statement was issued following Chancellor
Kenneth Clarke's last monthly monetary meeting before the general
election with Bank of England governor Eddie George Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although the minutes of Thursday's meeting will not be
published until the end of May, analysts believed that George was
most likely to have advised an increase in interest rates to guard
against inflation, as he has every month since November.
</P>
<P>
But Clarke was thought once again to have rejected the advise
because of the closeness of the general election.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that interest rates must rise whichever
party wins the general election after the next monetary meeting on
May 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
