<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-11 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM, Israel (Xinhua) -- Giant Belgian steel company,
Coqril Sambara, has made an initial venture into the Israel
market, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
Coqril has established a steel processing plant at Haifa
port together with Haifa-based construction material manufacturer,
Eders.
</P>
<P>
The initial investment in the new company called Edcastel
totals 8 million U.S. dollars, which will be covered in equal
parts by the two companies. The facility will be expanded at a
later stage, bringing the full cost past the 10 million dollars
mark.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli diamond industry achieved a dynamic
6.2 percent increase in polished diamond exports in the first two
months of 1997, with January-February sales exceeding 775
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of bi-weekly Israel Business attributed much of
the growth to increased sales to the U.S. and Hong Kong which
totaled 450 million and 170 million dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Israel Diamond Institute (IDI) Chairman, Moshe Schnitzer,
pointed out that buyers in the U.S. market expressed confidence
in Israel's ability to supply a comprehensive range of goods,
from mele'es to larger stones in all qualities.
</P>
<P>
Schnitzer added that the imminent political turnaround in Hong
Kong is not negatively impacting on the local market, and that
Israeli diamantaires are continuously expanding their marketing
network to relatively new consuming centers in southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of Israeli diamond cutters recently conducted
seminars on the polished diamond industry in Indonesia and the
Philippines under the auspices of the IDI.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 leaders of the diamond and fine jewelry trades
in both these relatively new markets attended the gatherings. In
view of the size of both markets, the event takes on considerable
importance.
</P>
<P>
Diamond industry is a major foreign currency earner for
Israel. The total exports in 1996 amounted to 3.998 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel is seeking gas imports from neighboring
Egypt despite new tension in the Arab-Israeli relations.
</P>
<P>
The local bi-weekly Israeli Business, which came off the press
today, reported that Israeli Minister of National Infrastructure
Ariel Sharon has met with Egyptian Ambassador to Israel Muhammad
Basyouni to express his country's willingness to start gas
business talks.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has added his weight to the
project following a discussion on the topic with President Hosni
Mubarak during his recent visit to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians have warned that they will offer their natural
gas resources to other countries than Israel if significant
headway is not achieved in peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has recently signed gas supply agreements with Jordan and
Turkey, although it is believed that Egypt could also meet
Israel's natural gas requirements if the political atmosphere
permits.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have reached a consensus on linking the
economic relations with Israel to the Middle East peace process, a
warning which seemed to be ignored so far by the Israeli
hardliners, now in power.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The contract signed by Iraq and Russia on developing
the West Al-Qaranah oilfield, the second phase, will be
implemented soon after being approved by the governments of both
countries, the Iraqi television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The television quoted Salman Negm, acting chief of the oil and
power committee of the Iraqi National Assembly, as saying that
during the term of the 23-year contract, the total production of
the oilfield is expected to reach 4.4 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
The West Al-Qaranah is one of the 10 oilfields that were marked
by Iraq for development during the last few years in cooperation
with major international companies from Russia, France and China.
</P>
<P>
The contract signed here in March on the heels of the second
session of the Iraqi-Russian Joint Committee for Economic, Trade
and Technical Cooperation, is expected to be implemented after the
U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq is lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
