<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Offers Aid to Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish government
agreed to assist Namibia's rural water supply and forestry
management programs, Southern African Broadcasting Association
(SABA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Finland will provide Namibia with nearly
nine million U.S. Dollars of aid.
</P>
<P>
About eight million U.S. Dollars will be used to finance a
forestry program in the next five years to address institutional
and social problems in the sector, SABA quoted informed sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The remaining sum goes to the Namibia's government scheme of
supplying water in the rural areas for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, with a population of 1.6 million, is one of the most
drought-prone countries in the Southern African region. Namibian
President Sam Nujoma declared last year a natural disaster
emergency in some parts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
