<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT on April 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- The first batch of Italian soldiers arrived in
Albania Friday to spearhead a multinational protection force that
aims to secure the country's key harbors and airports.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has sacked four top
Defense Ministry officials, including Commander of the Ground
Forces General Vladimir Semyonov and Chief of Naval Staff Admiral
Igor Khmelnov, the Presidential Office announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Passenger traffic resumed Friday on 100 long distance
routes in Albania, which closed in early March after an armed
revolt rocked the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- General Radovan Stojiccich, Deputy Interior
Minister of the Republic of Serbia of Yugoslavia, was assassinated
in Belgrade Friday.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Some 800 Iranians staged demonstrations Friday in
front of the German Embassy in Tehran to protest the Berlin court
ruling which charges top Iranian leaders with involvement in the
1992 murder of four Iranian dissidents.
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- The Government of National Unity and Reconciliation
of Angola was sworn in in Luanda Friday.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- An all-party meeting Friday reached a consensus on
the 1997-98 Union budget.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani Friday
blasted the Berlin court ruling on the assassination of four
Iranian-Kurdish dissidents, describing the court as "sinister" and
"disgraceful."
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Friday angrily rejected the EU stance to recall
all its ambassadors to Tehran and suspend critical dialogue with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- One craft of the Sri Lankan navy with eight military
personnel on board were captured Thursday by Tamil rebels in
Northern province, a military spokesman said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- With the backing of key opposition parties, a
government-proposed bill to revise a law to facilitate continued
compulsory land lease for the U.S. military in Okinawa was easily
passed Friday in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A senior Iranian official claimed Friday that the
Berlin Court ruling on the assassination of four Iranian
dissidents was devoid of any legal value.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's ruling African National Congress
has demanded fresh probe into the assassination of former South
African Communist Party leader Chris Hani, the local daily Sowetan
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia Friday welcomed Cuba's proposal to set
up a resident mission in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Zairean rebels have kidnaped some 60 Lebanese
nationals as they assembled at the airport in the southeastern
city of Lumumbashi before boarding a chartered plane for safety,
the Lebanese newspaper Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The European Union (EU) has begun to withdraw its
financial aid from Nigeria which had just turned down a
one-billion-U.S. Dollars loan of the EU for promotion of democracy
and human rights and alleviation of poverty in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel is seeking gas imports from neighboring
Egypt despite new tension in the Arab-Israeli relations, the local
bi-weekly Israeli Business reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- New efforts are reportedly being made to see if
the United Front and the Congress Party could get together again
as the Lower House began its debate on the one-line motion of
confidence moved by Prime Minister Deve Gowda Friday moring, Press
Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Deve Gowda Friday rejected
the demand by some leaders of the ruling United Front that he step
down to pave the way for a fresh understanding with the Congress
party for survival of the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Greek Air Force planes have violated Turkey's air
space 70 times in the past two years, including six in the first
three months of 1997, local newspaper Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
