<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension Should Not Hurt German-Iran Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- German-Iran business ties should not
be impaired by the mounting tension between the two countries
following the "Mykonos" trial in Berlin, Germany's top industrial
organization said today.
</P>
<P>
The German Council of Trade and Industry (DIHT), the umbrella
organization of chambers of commerce, said that a visit by a major
business delegation from Teheran would still go ahead as scheduled
on April 21-25.
</P>
<P>
The Iran delegation, made up of 26 representatives of various
chambers representing different sectors, is expected to visit
Dresden and Hamburg before meeting German companies at DIHT
headquarters in Bonn on April 23, Christoph Wolf, a DIHT official
said.
</P>
<P>
Wolf also said the DIHT was advising German companies to
maintain their business ties with Iran and not to be drawn into
political issues.
</P>
<P>
The DIHT statement came one day after the verdict in Berlin
against four men involved in the murder of four Kurdish opposition
figures in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court said Iranian leaders ordered the killings of
Sadegh Charafkandi, chief of the banned Democratic Kurdish Party
in Iran, and his three aides in 1992, a charge rejected by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Following this, both Germany and Iran have recalled their
ambassadors and expelled four diplomats from each other's
capitals. The European Union (EU) also reacted with a mass recall
of ambassadors and suspension of dialogue with Iran.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Ministry spokesman, Martin Erdmann, stressed
today that the EU dialogue with Iran was only suspended, not
permanently cancelled. He did not specify how long the suspension
would last.
</P>
<P>
"It is not in our interest in the current situation to pour oil
onto the fire," he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is currently Iran's biggest trading partner in Europe,
with its exports to Iran reaching 2.2 billion marks (about 1.3
billion U.S. dollars) in 1996. Imports from Iran were 1.1 billion
marks (650 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
