<HEADLINE> Irish Government Unveils Computer Education Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government has announced
a 30 million pound (about 48 million U.S. dollar) five-year
investment program in an effort to bring more computer education
into schools.
</P>
<P>
The scheme called Schools IT 2000, which will train 14,000
teachers in information technology education, is designed to get a
computer with internet access into every primary and secondary
school by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the program's introduction ceremony Thursday, Irish
Prime Minister John Bruton said the program could allow Ireland to
take full advantage of the economic, social and educational
benefits of the information society.
</P>
<P>
"We need to be in the forefront of these technologies by moving
forward through three or four stages of technology development in
one leap," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 48-million-dollar budget is to be divided with half for
computer equipment and half for the training of teachers and the
development of practices and curriculum products to be used in
school education programs.
</P>
<P>
Joe O'Toole, general secretary of the Irish National Teachers
Organization, said the project, which "we have been calling for
for quite some time" was "a great advance to bring primary schools
into the next millennium."
</P>
<P>
However, he said one computer per school was not enough to
provide "adequate computer education" for large numbers of
students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
