<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Unity Government Takes Office to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Angola's government of national
unity and reconciliation was sworn in here today to cement peace
after nearly two decades of civil war in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
"It could make a definite contribution to a better solution,"
said President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos in a speech at a ceremony
attended by 13 foreign heads of state.
</P>
<P>
"The formation of this government is another fundamental step
in a long and difficult process of peace," said the president.
"Behind us lie thousands of dead, a devastated country and a
semi-paralysed economy," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Jonas Savimbi, leader of the former rebel movement, the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), did
not show up. He was represented at the ceremony by Antonio Dembo,
his deputy.
</P>
<P>
Eleven UNITA members joined the unity government which has a
total of 80 officials including 28 ministers.
</P>
<P>
UNITA has been given four portfolios in the unity cabinet --
ministers of geology and mining, health, commerce and tourism,
while most of the ministrial portfolios were taken by the ruling
Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA).
</P>
<P>
UNITA leader Savimbi himself has been appointed "president of
the largest opposition party", a post that carries the right to
regular consultation with President Dos Santos and an official
residence in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
According to President Dos Santos, top tasks facing the
newly-inaugurated unity government include the formation process
of the united army, clearing of millions of land mines planted
during the civil war, repatriation of refugees, and a vast task
of rebuilding the devastated national economy.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony today was the culmination of a peace process
which began in November 1994 when the two sides signed a peace
accord in Lusaka, Zambia.
</P>
<P>
MPLA and UNITA went to war with each other shortly after
independence in 1975, turning the oil-and-diamond-rich country
into one of Africa's war field.
</P>
<P>
United Nations officials this week unveiled a plan to begin
demobilizing some 40,000 UNITA fighters on Saturday. The soldiers
have spent months in U.N. assembly areas.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign heads of state watching were President Jorge
Sampaio of Portugal, President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and
President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, special representative of U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, also congratulated the swearing-in of the unity
government.
</P>
<P>
"A stable, lasting peace should allow greater exploitation of
the country's largely unexplored mineral wealth and could bring
greater regulation to diamond mining, now largely the realm of
freelancers under UNITA control," said an observer closerly
watching the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
