<HEADLINE> Foreign Leaders Congratulate on Angola's Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign leaders today
congratulated on the inauguration of Angola's unity government,
which they said would cement peace after nearly 20 years of civil
war in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
"This is a historical development," Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, who is also chairman of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to which Angola is a member, said in
a speech delivered to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Peace in Angola would not only help rebuild the devastated
economy in the country, but would also foster regional stability
in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary-General of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), told the ceremony that today would be
remembered by the Angolan history as "a turning point".
</P>
<P>
President Jorge Sampaio of Portugal, President Nelson Mandela
of South Africa were among the 13 foreign heads of state
attending the swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, special representative of United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, also attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some foreign governments sent telegraphs of
congratulation to the newly-formed unity government.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said in a telegraph that
his government would continue to provide financial support to
Angola's peace process and would be willing to help the country's
national reconstruction process.
</P>
<P>
Angola's government of national unity and reconciliation was
sworn in here today to cement peace after nearly two decades of
civil war in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony today was the culmination of a peace process
which began in November 1994 when the two sides signed a peace
accord in Lusaka, Zambia. 
</P>
