<HEADLINE> S. Africa Considered New Venue of AIDS Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa was considered
as the venue of a new AIDS research center, Luc Montagnier, head
of the World Foundation of AIDS Research and Prevention, said in
Pretoria today.
</P>
<P>
Montagnier said his foundation had to learn more about the
natural history of AIDS in Africa in order to design new and
affordable treatments for the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
Montagnier, a Frenchman who had discovered the AIDS virus,
said South Africa had over the past five years seen the fastest
growth in the disease on the continent.
</P>
<P>
An estimated two million people have currently been infected
with HIV virus which causes AIDS throughout South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new AIDS research center would be provided with
public and private funding, and linked to a similar one in the
west African country of Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Montagnier and representatives of South African medical
organizations were currently touring the country to find a
suitable site for the proposed AIDS research center, which should
be close to a hospital and a university. 
</P>
</TEXT>
