<HEADLINE> International Media Women's Meeting Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The week-long biennial meeting of
the International Association of Women in Radio and Television
(IAWRT) closed today in Darwendale, Zimbabwe, calling for
increased solidarity among media women.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was jointly hosted by the IAWRT and the Federation
of African Media Women for the first time in the African
continent with 70 participants from African, European and Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
IAWRT is an organization of professionals in broadcasting or
related fields from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The delegates discussed the impact of women professionals in
the electronic media field and sought to utilize the professional
skills of the members to support women in development.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, IAWRT president Christina Ruhnbro
expressed concern that a Zambian government proposal to retrench
untrained journalists would have drastic effects on women in the
media who she said were "the most vulnerable to such moves."
</P>
<P>
She said the decision to retrench journalists without formal
degrees would prejudice women journalists who rely on experience
rather than formal training for their profession. 
</P>
