<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Returns Home After Visit to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 11 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan returned
home today after concluding his 21-day visit to the United States,
Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the king held discussions on the stalemated
Middle East peace process with U.S. President Bill Clinton,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting between Hussein and Clinton, the
U.S. government promised to present a new serious formula to the
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government also decided to sell subsidized wheat flour
and corn to Jordan and extend credit to Jordan for purchasing
other commodities as part of U.S. assistance to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Washington also agreed to support Jordan's efforts to
reschedule its debts due for repayment between June 1997 and June
1999.
</P>
<P>
The king discussed the peace process and other issues related
to Jordanian-U.N. relations during his talks with Annan on March
31.
</P>
<P>
But the king's talks with Netanyahu on the peace process after
his surgery scored no achievements, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On April 5, the king underwent a surgery at Mayo Clinic,
Minnesota, to remove a proportion of his prostate gland which became
enlarged and caused him some difficulty in urinating.
</P>
<P>
Hussein said that "the surgery was not easy, but it was
successful and its results were positive."
</P>
<P>
The king's visit to the U.S. came against the background that
Israeli construction of Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
triggered widespread protest from the Palestinians and the peace
process was seriously threatened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
