<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dangers of UK's Unbalanced Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Many of Britain's economists are
worrying that the shape of growth in its economy in recent months
is becoming increasingly unbalanced.
</P>
<P>
While the latest evidence on consumer activity has reflected a
sign of overheating in Britain's economy, the continued strength
of the pound has even cast a dark cloud over recovery in its
industry.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of the year, strong evidence showed that
1997 will still very much be the year of the consumer.
</P>
<P>
The most visible indication of rising consumer activity is the
strength of spending in the high street, with retail sales growing
at over 4 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
The strong consumer activity has been backed up by record
consumer borrowing and the continued recovery in the housing
market.
</P>
<P>
Official figures released Thursday showing further house price
increases and rising national construction order books emphasized
the strength of recovery in these markets.
</P>
<P>
House prices nationally rose 7.2 percent over the year and by
11 percent in the first quarter. The average price of a UK home in
the first quarter was 66,899 pounds (107,040 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
While the consumer sector has continued to gather pace,
industry has looked far less healthy.
</P>
<P>
Although recent months have seen an upturn in the growth of
manufacturing output owing to the increase of domestic demand, the
warning signs are obvious.
</P>
<P>
The export orders balance of the Confederation of British
Industry survey has dropped to its lowest level for three years,
while manufacturing investment is falling sharply.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, Roger Bootle and Jonathan Loynes, co-editors of
HSBC Markets wrote in an article entitled "UK Economic Prospects,"
"It would be no surprise if output growth were to slow quite
sharply over the summer as sterling's strength really starts to
bite into competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, people are bound to ask: what would
happen to Britain's economy if the growth is unbalanced?
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there seems to be few ill-effects as yet,
inflation is low and falling, and unemployment is dropping.
</P>
<P>
But economists from the City argue: the current favorable
economic situation in Britain underlines precisely the importance
of avoiding unbalanced growth because they were made possible by
the very sort of balanced growth conditions which now look to be
at risk.
</P>
<P>
They believe that stronger domestic demand in Britain will soon
start to pull in more imports, while the growth of exports is
already slowing in response to the stronger pound. By the second
half of the year, the trade position could be worsening
considerably.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that all of this will present a serious policy
dilemma for the next government, whichever party forms it.
</P>
<P>
There is little doubt that the new government will be anxious
to avoid overheating in the consumer sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
