<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Curb Monopolistic Tendencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Plans are at an advanced stage to
set up a regulatory authority to curb restrictive business
practices in Zimbabwe, Deputy Minister of Industry and Commerce
Obert Mpofu said here today.
</P>
<P>
Mpofu said that the Industry and Trade Competition Commission
will be formed once an act has been passed by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mpofu said the government is against monopolistic tendencies
in the economy and will ensure that consumers are not unfairly
treated by local companies.
</P>
<P>
"The commission will serve to curb restrictive business
practices and control abuses of monopoly power and sanction
mergers and takeover," Mpofu said.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry will not neglect its obligation to
protect the interests and rights of consumers, adding it is now
geared to play a more pro-active rather than a reactive role in
the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
