<HEADLINE> S. African Firm Accused of Subverting Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Defense Minister
Philemon Malima said today that a South African company which
recruits mercenaries was involved in mobilizing disgruntled
former soldiers to destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence reports show Executive Outcomes, a military
employment agency in South Africa, is enticing some Namibians to
undergo military training in Sierra Leone with the intentions of
destabilizing the country, the Southern African Broadcasting
Association quoted Malima as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing parliament, Malima said Hans Dreyer, former leader
of the South African police counter-insurgency unit Koevoet, was
involved in the operation. He also assured the nation that the
situation is under control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Executive Outcomes rejected the claim that it was
involved in the subversive activities in Namibia, stressing it
had no connection with Dreyer.
</P>
<P>
"The corporation strongly condemns and indeed resists such
activities on the continent of Africa and elsewhere," Executive
Outcomes said in a statement in Pretoria, capital of South
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
