<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Proposes Rapprochement Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has put forward a detailed proposal that could
contribute toward rapprochement between Greek and Turkish
Cypriots, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Manolis Chritstofides
said "the measures are neither spasmodic nor temporary, and
could lead to positive steps toward rapprochement."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government supports reconciliation between the two
communities on the island, Chritstofides stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to give further details about the
measures, saying only that the Cypriot government is expecting the
U.N. to reply.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.N.-led proximity talks between the two
sides aimed at paving the way for direct talks between
President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash,
Christofides said there are some encouraging developments.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that "we have not yet reached the desired
point that would allow face-to-face negotiations." Efforts must
continue, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The ground for direct talks has to be prepared in the best
possible way and we all have to speak the same language,
otherwise another round of negotiations, just for the sake of
negotiations, will take place," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said when the proximity talks end, the government will
assess the outcome and decide "whether what we have before us is
what we want to begin direct negotiations."
</P>
<P>
In the past three weeks, U.N. Resident Representative Gustave
Feissel has been holding bi-weekly separate meetings with
President Clerides and Denktash in a bid to prepare the ground
for face-to-face negotiations, which is likely to take place in
June.
</P>
<P>
Feissel today briefed President Clerides on last Wednesday's
meeting in Geneva between U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
In a statement upon his return Thursday from Geneva, where he
attended the Annan-Denktash meeting, Feissel said progress has
been made in the proximity talks between President Clerides and
Denktash on both the substance of the Cyprus problem and the
mutual good-will gestures.
</P>
<P>
He also said Annan is keen on getting Denktash and Clerides to
face-to-face talks by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash have not met since October 1994 when
the two men held two rounds of informal talks here under
the U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup.  
</P>
</TEXT>
