<HEADLINE> Greece Supports Proximity Talks in Cyprus: Senior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Greek Deputy Foreign Minister
Yiannos Kranidiotis today expressed the hope that the ongoing
U.N.-led proximity talks between Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will be
fruitful and lead to face-to-face talks.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis, who arrived here Thursday night for a four-day
working visit, made the remarks after a meeting with President
Clerides.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he discussed with Clerides
developments in the Cyprus problem and Cyprus' bid to become a
full member of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Greek official expressed the hope that the proximity
talks "will be fruitful and eventually lead to the start of a
face-to-face dialogue, in order to reach a just and viable
solution to the Cyprus problem, based on the U.N. resolutions
and decisions."
</P>
<P>
He noted that despite some difficulties, Cyprus' course to
join the EU continues "smoothly."
</P>
<P>
Accession negotiations will begin as scheduled, six months
after the end of the Intergovernmental Conference, with the
legitimate government of Cyprus, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis said he conveyed to President Clerides Greece's
full support to the Cypriot struggle.
</P>
<P>
The Greek official congratulated Cyprus' new Foreign Minister
Yiannakis Cassoulides, who replaced Alecos Michaelides in last
Monday's cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Turkey and Britain were guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 Treaty of Establishment of the
Cyprus Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
