<HEADLINE> Writethru: Indian PM Loses Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister H.D. Deve
Gowda today lost a vote of confidence in his 10-month-old
government, paving the way for the ruling United Front and the
Congress party to negotiate a solution to the current political
crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was provoked by the Congress Party President Sitaram
Kesri who withdrew the party's support to the government on March
30, accusing it of failing to check the rise of communal forces
such as the Bharatiya Janata Party and making efforts to
marginalize the party.
</P>
<P>
President Shanker Dayal Sharma set today the deadline for Deve
Gowda to seek a vote of confidence in his government in the Lok
Sabha (the lower house of parliament).
</P>
<P>
The prime minister moved a motion in a special sitting of the
lower house today after the 13-party United Front and the Congress
party failed to reach a compromise in spite of two rounds of
formal talks between them.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party had demanded the removal of Gowda as an
precondition for any future arrangement. But the United Front had
categorically ruled out any change in its leadership.
</P>
<P>
The motion was defeated with 158 for, 292 against and six in
absence in a total of 456 votes.
</P>
<P>
The 11th Lok Sabha has an effective strength of 543 seats,
excluding two vacancies.
</P>
<P>
After being defeated in the lower house of parliament, Gowda
said that he was not recommending the dissolution of parliament to
the president.
</P>
<P>
The UF Steering Committee will be meeting early tomorrow
morning amidst speculations that it might elect a new leader to
revive the relationship with the Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the biggest opposition party
in the country, has said that it would not stake claim to form the
next government unless it was sure of commanding majority support
in parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
