<HEADLINE> Lebanon Seeks Help for Release of Hostages in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz confirmed here today that a number of Lebanese citizens
had been taken hostage in Zaire and the government was seeking
international help for their release.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star, the only English daily in Beirut, reported
that Zairean rebels kidnapped 60 Lebanese citizens assembling at
the airport in the southeastern city of Lubumbashi for a French
charter plane Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebels rounded up all the 60 passengers, stripped them
of their passports and luggage and led them away to an unknown
destination, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"There are a number of Lebanese citizens held as hostages in
Zaire and they have been asked to pay a sum of money to be set
free," the Lebanese foreign minister told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We are in continuous contacts with a number of countries but
it has turned out that few of these countries can do something at
Lubumbashi," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made a lot of contacts with the French on this issue,
and I made additional calls this morning. But we were informed
that France's influence and power was in Kinshasa and outside of
Lubumbashi," Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister promised to conduct more contacts,
probably with the United States and Belgium, for an evacuation of
the Lebanese who want to leave that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
