<HEADLINE> Turkey to Spend 31-Billion-Dollar on Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will spend 31 billion
U.S. dollars on the defense modernization program for the next
decade in an effort to enhance the Turkish armed forces' combat
capabilities, a high-ranking official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Defense Minister Turhan Tayan
said that the program would foresee the acquisition of thousands
of armored combat vehicles, attack helicopters, main battle
tanks, warships, missiles as well as communication systems.
</P>
<P>
This 10-year defense program will also involves the
continuation of the modernization of Turkish Air Force's fighter
planes, Tayan said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his ministry would present the detailed plan to
private sector in order to draw their attention to the defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
Tayan said that the government would provide financial
support to local companies which were willing to be involved in
the projects to increase the share of domestic capital in the
country's defense industry sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized the importance of setting up Turkey's
own defense industry system, adding that Turkey had drawn a lesson
from the U.S. arms embargo on Ankara following a Turkish
military intervention in Cyprus in 1974.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government would pay attention to the
defense industry, in which great strides had been made during the
past years.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, a report prepared by the military
authorities said that 150 billion U.S. dollars would be needed
to fund the arms procurement and operation of the Turkish Armed
Forces for the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
As a military power in the region, Turkey has the second
largest force in NATO, trailing only the United States in the
number of troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
