<HEADLINE> French, Belgian Service Companies Merge to Build </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS. April 11 (Xinhua) -- The service company of Compagnie de
Suez and the water company Lyonnaise des Eaux today agreed to
merge to create a French-Belgian giant concern of services ranging
from electricity to communication.
</P>
<P>
The new concern, to be named Suez-Lyonnaise, will be formally
set up by the end of June, will have 190,000 employees in more
than 100 countries around the world, and an annual turnover of 210
billion francs (42 billion U.S. dollars), said company sources.
</P>
<P>
The administrative councils of the two companies said today
here that the Suez-Lyonnais has the ambition of becoming the
world's number one company of "collective services of proximity"
covering services in energy, water, cleaning and communication.
</P>
<P>
"The creation of a European group of world vocation is full of
sense because it responds to the evolution of the demand and to
the nature of competition," said the president of Lyonnaise des
Eaux, Jerome Monod.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Mestrallet, the president of Suez, will be the
operational director of the future group, while Monod will be the
president of the council of supervision of the group, which will
represent the interests of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The Compagnie de Suez was created 140 years ago by Ferdinand de
Lesseps to open up the Suez Canal linking the Mediterranean with
the Red Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
