<HEADLINE> EU-U.S. Deal on Helms-Burton Should Apply to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The deal between European Union
(EU) and the United States on the Helms-Burton Act should apply to
Canada or to any other country, a senior Canadian official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The European Union reached a deal today with the U.S. on their
dispute over the anti-Cuban legislation, which seeks to punish
foreign companies doing business on the Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the EU said it intends to withdraw its complaint
before the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The union had accused the U.S. of violating international trade
rules by seeking to impose its policies beyond U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
"We insist that it apply to Canada or any other country and I
think the way the law's written it would have to anyway," Canadian
Trade Minister Art Eggleton said today.
</P>
<P>
"The law of Helms-Burton will not provide for discriminatory
procedure relevant to some countries and not others," Eggleton was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Canada has been fighting against the U.S. act from the very
beginning.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen Canadian businessmen have been barred from the
U.S. because of their links with Cuban-related businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
