<HEADLINE> Clinton Says No Change in Cuba Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today said that there will be no change in the U.S. embargo policy
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Clinton accused Cuba of "illegally" shooting down two planes
early last year. The U.S. enacted the Helms-Burton law
strengthening sanctions against Cuba after its forces shot down
the two light planes entering Cuba from the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Speaking before a luncheon of the American Society of
Newspapers Editors, Clinton firmly defended U.S. policy towards
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy toward Cuba today therefore is one that is dictated
by Cuba not by the United States. And until I see some indication
of willingness to change, it's going to be very difficult to
persuade me to change our policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed by the U.S. on Cuba have been strongly
criticized all over the world, particularly after the Helms-Burton
Act was enacted. The European Union has requested the World Trade
Organization to make a verdict on the controversial law.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels today, the European Union (EU) announced that it
has struck a deal with the U.S. over the row, which could lead to
amendment of the Helms-Burton law. 
</P>
