Prodi's minority government was forced into the test after the
Refoundation Communist Party, led by former Prime Minister Silvio
Berlusconi, abandoned Prodi in a parliamentary vote Wednesday on
sending Italian troops to Albania as part of a 6,000-strong
multinational force to aid the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
The government-dominated Senate had given its support to Prodi
over the Albanian mission, which is due to swing into action next
week.
</P>
<P>
Prodi came to power last May but has always struggled to get
along with his troublesome ally -- the Refoundation Communist
Party. Other coalition partners have threatened to quit the
government if Prodi fails to reach an accord with the Refoundation
Communist Party on future policy goals. 
