</P>
<P>
It is significant that the PLC has passed the first and second
readings of a bill from the Secretary of Justice of the HKSAR,
namely the "Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill."
</P>
<P>
The readings of the bill at the plenary session of the PLC
marked the start of the PLC's function to enact laws for Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
On April 10, the HKSAR Chief Executive's Office published the
Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill, which provides for several
additional holidays in the remainder of 1997 and for the general
holidays in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the HKSAR Chief Executive's Office has also issued a
 consultative document on the proposals for the amendments to the
Societies Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance in Hong Kong
and it is expected to be presented to the PLC in the coming months
 after the office solicits Hong Kong people's suggestions.
</P>
<P>
All the developments have indicated that with the approaching
of Hong Kong's return to the motherland, the PLC is accelerating
its work in legislation for the future HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Besides enacting laws, the 60-member PLC elected on December
21, 1996 will shoulder heavy tasks to examine and approve the
1997-1998 budget to be submitted by the HKSAR government, approve
the appointment of the judges of the Court of Final Appeal and the
 Chief Justice of the High court of the HKSAR as well as to debate
 policy address to be delivered by the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, the PLC has made preparations for its
 missions.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the council adopted "the Rules of Procedure
 of the PLC" and passed the amendments to "the Resolution on
Registration of Members' Interests," which represents another
major progress in the PLC's work.
</P>
<P>
"The Rules of Procedure" will ensure the PLC to work
effectively up to June 30, 1998 when the First Legislature of the
HKSAR is to be elected whereas "the Resolution on Registration of
Members' Interests" will enhance the transparency of the council,
which is necessary for the PLC in its commitment to the
implementation of the principle of "Hong Kong people governing
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
With Leong Che-hung and Ip Kwok-him elected chairman and deputy
 chairman of the PLC's House Committee, and Ronald Arculli and
Henry Wu as chairman and deputy chairman of the Finance Committee
at today's meeting, the PLC is mature to play its role in its
legislative work for the establishment of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Wong, president of the current Legislative Council and
member of the PLC, said that today's meeting is fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Wong especially talked about Leong Che Hung being both the
chairman of the House Committee of the PLC of the HKSAR and the
existing Legislative Council, adding, "That will be helpful to the
 PLC's work."
</P>
<P>
PLC member Yeung Chun Kam said that time is pressing for the
PLC to fulfill its tasks in line with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
He said that today's election for heads of the two committees
represented the trust of the PLC members in them and it also
demonstrated the cooperative attitude in the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
