<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Youth Misbehavior Rouses Social Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An attempt by a Kuwaiti
secondary school student to gun down his Egyptian teacher
Wednesday have roused great concern about rising crime and
declining morality of the young generation in the small Islamic
state.
</P>
<P>
Just because his science teacher failed him in geology, a
15-year old student Wednesday shot twice and seriously injured the
teacher, Mutaz Mahmoud Ibrahim, 35, on the Asmaei Secondary School
campus.
</P>
<P>
The teacher who was injured in his stomach, lung and liver is
still in critical condition and under treatment in a hospital's
intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti scholars and officials express their great distress over
surging violence among Kuwaiti youth which they described as
dangerous and detrimental to the social moral.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Education Minister Abdullah Al-Ghuneim described the
unprecedented incident in Kuwait's history as "strange and
contradictory to our traditions and values and something the
Kuwaiti society is unfamiliar with."
</P>
<P>
Sociologists believed that the incident is only the tip of the
ice-burg of crime in the country, of which the crime rate is about
one percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Such incidents have made Kuwaitis raise questions on whether
the country should do more to shore up the stability of a
traditional Muslim society and impose tougher penalties on the
criminals.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that there are two main causes of the
misbehaviors of the youths. On one hand, the sudden abundance of
wealth caused by the oil boom has ensured a luxury life enjoyed by
the younger generation. This has resulted in lack of spiritual
ballast in their minds. On the other, many bad western ideas have
entered Kuwaiti people's minds since the 1990 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
An associate professor of sociology in Kuwait University told
Xinhua that the phenomena of selfishness, laziness, clannishness
and chasing sumptuosity are common among youngsters. Cases of
drug addiction, murder and rape committed by the youngsters are
often reported in local media.
</P>
<P>
Only in October 1995, some 4,500 juvenile delinquents were
involved in 2,500 judicial cases.
</P>
<P>
But some consider the case from another angle. They say the
government should set up more recreational facilities in the small
country with few parks or sports grounds to attract more youngsters
to do healthy activities in their spare time. "The youths are
filled with energy, but they have no place to go," a clinical
psychologist told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He complained that at nights, especially on holidays, groups of
car-crazing Kuwaiti youngsters are seen roaring up and down the
main highways in cars and motorcycles with extra high-speed.
</P>
<P>
Still, many put the blame on the large number of illegal owning
of weapons among the Kuwaiti people resulted from the 1990 Iraqi
invasion. At the end of the war, fleeing Iraqis left a huge
quantity of weapons and ammunitions in Kuwait. Many of the guns
have yet to be handed to the government in spite of the
government's appeals.
</P>
<P>
The situation is critical enough for the government and
National Assembly to tackle the problem of juvenile delinquency on
a firm footing, a parliamentary member Hassan Jawhar was quoted as
saying by the Arab Times.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti parliamentary members have called on imposing a
mandatory death sentence for drug trafficking and drug abuse in
which many youngsters were involved in.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, officials and educationists called on parents
to monitor their children more closely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
