<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Ease Closure on West Bank, Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army is to ease a
three-week total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, allowing
a limited number of Palestinians to enter Israel for work.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report, the decision to ease
the closure was made by Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, and it
will take effect Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Sunday morning, 20,000 Palestinian workers from
the West Bank and Gaza Strip will be permitted to enter Israel,
said the report. It added that the permit will only be given to
married men over the age of 45.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel imposed the total closure on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip immediately after a suicide bombing attack
in a downtown coffee shop in Tel Aviv, which left three
women dead and over 50 injured.
</P>
<P>
The closure has barred tens of thousands of Palestinians
from returning to their jobs inside Israel, and from traveling
between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Israeli army allowed Gaza Strip
residents in the West Bank to return to the strip, as well
as West Bank residents in the Gaza Strip to travel home.
</P>
<P>
The army was also allowing Palestinians who are married to
Jerusalem residents with Israeli identity cards to enter the
city.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, 22 more Palestinian ambulances were allowed to
enter Israel on an emergency basis, bringing to 36 the
number of ambulances allowed to traverse Israel between the
Palestinian autonomous areas.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said that 100 Palestinian laborers who have
jobs in tourist industries were also allowed entry into Israel,
but it stressed that all entrance permits are subjected to strict
security clearances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
