<HEADLINE> Hongkong-Funded Wharf Being Built in Southeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on a 25,000-ton
wharf, costing more than 24 million US dollars, is being built in
southeast China's Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
The multi-purpose Chengan wharf is in Dongshan County on the
west of Dongshan Island, and is believed to provide the shortest
distance in the province to Taiwan, Macao, and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Dongshan Island, one of the country's category-one ports open
to the outside, now has two 5,000-ton wharfs and one 3,000-ton
petroleum wharf.
</P>
<P>
The new wharf is scheduled to have an annual 1.1 million-ton
handling capacity in two years, and to boost development of rich
silica sand resources on the island. 
</P>
