<HEADLINE> Turin Shroud Escapes Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ROME, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Shroud of Turin, revered by
many Roman Catholics as the burial cloth of Jesus Christ, narrowly
escaped incineration today when a fire gutted the chapel where it
is housed.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters braved scorching heat to carry out a silver box
containing the shroud, a piece of cloth bearing the stained image
of a crucified man believed by many faithful to be Christ.
</P>
<P>
The shroud, 4.4 meter by 1.4 meter, was taken from the Middle
East by the crusaders in 1353 and housed in a chapel in France. It
was transferred to Turin after being slightly damaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
Always revered in Italy, the shroud gained world fame at the
end of last century, when a photographic negative revealed the
image on it which is invisible to the naked eyes.
</P>
<P>
Fire officials said the blaze also caused considerable damage
to part of an adjacent museum.
</P>
<P>
The police said there were no injuries.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire, which broke out late Friday,is
unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
