<HEADLINE> Iraqi Press: Annan Expects Renewal of Oil-for-Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
expects that the U.N. Security Council Sanctions Committee will
renew the oil-for-food deal with Iraq for another six-month term,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi newspaper Babel carried a story on the deal, which has
alleviated the sufferings of the Iraqi people since its
enforcement last December.
</P>
<P>
Annan was quoted by the Iraqi paper as saying that "in my
personal estimation, the current term of the agreement will be
extended for another six months soon after its termination in
June" as long as the conditions that facilitated its signing
remain.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-Iraq deal allowed Iraq last December to sell 2 billion
dollars worth of oil every six months to buy badly-need foodstuffs
and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the purchased foodstuffs and medicine
arrived in Iraq on March 20 under the deal, the current term of
which will expire by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
The volume of the foodstuffs that have been transported to Iraq
under the deal has so far reached 200,000 tonnes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
