<HEADLINE> Many Nairobi City Buildings Risk Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan official has said that
55 percent of Nairobi city had informal settlements where no
standards of construction were applicable, Kenya Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a Presidential Commission of Inquiry as
saying on Friday that many urban dwellers in Kenya's capital city
are sitting on a time bomb due to the existing sub-standard
buildings.
</P>
<P>
The commission noted that an earthquake measuring between four
and five on the Richter scale would demolish thousands of
residential buildings in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
A group of officials led by the Commission Chairman Reuben
Mutiso pointed out that some of the buildings emerging in the
recent past lacked reinforced foundation and support structure
after they conducted a public inspection of houses in the city on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mutiso said that many buildings "are not engineered, nor
supervised and the very elements of construction are not looked
into when approving them."
</P>
<P>
During the tour, he said, the commission had discovered there
were a number tall buildings whose fire escapes were locked up
and some others had no fire escapes at all.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city's central business district buildings have
not been maintained for a long time, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Commission of Inquiry was appointed by Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi following the Sunbeam Supermarket disaster in
which 16 people were killed when the building's canopy collapsed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
