<HEADLINE> ROK Wins Large Gas Storage Facility Bid in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- LG Corporation, one of the
Republic of Korea's largest industrial groups, announced here
today that it has won bidding on a 100-million-US-dollar contract
to build a large Chinese gas storage facility.
</P>
<P>
LG Engineering Co., one of its subsidiaries, beat out 13
international companies for a contract to design and build a large
liquefied natural gas storage facility for the US's Caltex in
Shantou, a coastal city in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
It has two 100,000-cubic-meter facilities underground and an
office center. It will be the first underground gas storage
facility in a cave, and is said by LG to be the country's largest
state-of-the-art facility. It is scheduled to be operational in
1998.
</P>
<P>
LG is the third largest corporation in the ROK, with revenues
of 72 billion dollars last year. It already has production plants
in 12 Chinese cities. 
