<HEADLINE> Stalled Mideast Peace process to Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 12 (Xinhua) - Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali said here today that the currently stalled Middle East
peace process would be eventually moving forward.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides are still working on it to seek for concrete
ideas," though no new initiatives were produced during King of
Jordan Hussein's recent visit to the United States." said Majali
who accompanied Hussein during the visit from March 21 to April 11.
</P>
<P>
"It is critical at this moment, but I do not think it will
stay like this for long," said Majali.
</P>
<P>
Majali, who was named prime minister by the king last month for
the second time, negotiated and later signed Jordan's peace treaty
with Israel in 1994 during his first tenure from May 1993 to
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The current impasse was attributed to Israeli government's
decision to build 6,500 Jewish housings in Arab East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians want to be the capital of their future state,
said the prime Minister
</P>
<P>
Jordan would do all it could to help the Palestinian people
regain their legitimate rights and exercise their
self-determination on their own soil, said Majali.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also urged the U.S. to play "active partner"
role to offer of solutions to help the Palestinians and Israelis
to carry on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Every problem has a solution," said Majali, confident that
the peace process would be reactivated again.
</P>
<P>
As to the issue of Iraq, Majali said that Jordan wanted the
United Nations sanctions imposed on Baghdad following its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990 to be lifted soon to end the suffering of the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"But at the same time, we would like to see Iraq comply with
all related U.N. Security Council resolutions," he said, adding
this includes the dismantling of all weapons of mass destruction,
Long-range missiles and paying for war reparations. 
</P>
