<HEADLINE> Jordan's PM: Economy in Recess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 12 (Xinhua) - Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali acknowledged here today that his country's economy was in
recess and investment did not move forward in a satisfactory way.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is red tape, pledging to remove all
obstacles facing economic development.
</P>
<P>
The government would encourage people to invest outside Amman,
the capital, through offering incentives, providing necessary
infrastructure and adopting a centralized policy, Majali told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
In summary, Majali vowed to give high priority to economic
development and social progress in his country.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Jordanian citizens to move to work and not
let the foreign labor to further grow in their country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, non-Jordanian workers are
costing the country more than 500 million Jordanian dinars (about
714 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
This might be one of the main solutions to unemployment and
poverty which were ravaging the country's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has promised to accelerate the economic reform
through legislation. It also urged the private sector to launch
economic and trade projects in different governorates.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Jordan enjoyed a flourishing economy on the
basis of foreign aids. It began to lose foreign aids when the Gulf
crisis broke out for it sided with Iraq. Since then, the country,
scant of natural resources and without oil, has suffered from
economic recession.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister resumed office last month with a pledge to
speed up the economic reform, probably in a different way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
