<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why China Practices Direct Election of Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China is pushing a democratic
system with Chinese characteristics in its vast rural areas and
experts say that this new system of farmers directly electing
village committees has deep social roots.
</P>
<P>
The practice began after the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress passed a law on village committees in November
1987, and has since spread to 18 Chinese provinces,
municipalities, and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the new system came, first of all, from
economic reforms begun in the countryside in the late 1970s. These
rural reforms introduced a household-based contract responsibility
system, and have had profound effects on rural economic relations
and the social structure, and provided a solid foundation for
direct election of village committees.
</P>
<P>
A village committe is a self-governing organization that
oversees public affairs and public welfare, mediates civil
disputes, maintains public order, and assists the township
government.
</P>
<P>
The contract responsibility system, which has helped Chinese
farmers prosper, has produced a new pattern of economic relations
and new ownership relations in the countryside, which combined to
create the need for a new mechanism to oversee different interests.
</P>
<P>
The system has also given farmers considerable power in
distributing rural resources, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
In the past, collectives like People's Communes used to have
distribution rights and peasants used to get grain and money from
the collectives. Today, the farmers work on contracts and pay
taxes and fees to the State and the collective.
</P>
<P>
In many parts of China where there are few township
enterprises, the collective relies on farmers, financially and in
terms of labor, for public-interest work, like road building, the
experts point out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why China Practices Direct Election of Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Relations between the State, the collective, and farmers have
become more direct under the contract responsibility system,
making farmers more concerned about village and financial affairs
and about the use of money collected from them.
</P>
<P>
The rural social structure in China has over the years
undergone great changes, as is reflected in the large-scale
movemetns of farmers between different regions and in
diversification among farmers. Nowadays, some work the soil,
others work in township enterprises, some serve as employees of
private business, others run industrial and commercial businesses
on their own or by hiring others, and still others manage village
affairs and collective enterprises.
</P>
<P>
This is a good means of balanced relations between various
social groups in rural areas by a democratic form of
self-management by farmers, the experts note.
</P>
<P>
They say that changes in the political structure of rural areas
since 1978, when China started its reform and opening-up drive,
have made it possible for farmers to elect the village committee
directly.
</P>
<P>
Because they are no longer ties to the land and because they
have more understanding of the law, Chinese farmers have developed
a need to have their opinions on issues like the management of
village affairs listened to.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the emergence of some social problems in rural
areas, like social security, financial management, and the
relationship between cadres and the people, can only be
fundamentally resolved through democratic self-management and
farmers' direct participation in the grass-roots management, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
To meet the needs of the new situation, the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress passed a law on organizing
village committees, stating that the director, deputy directors,
and members of the village committee should be elected by the
villagers for a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
From 1988 to early this year, 18 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions held three direct elections of village
committees, and other provinces and regions held two. Eastern
Fujian and northeastern Heilongjiang provinces held a fourth
series of direct elections in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Records show that China had 930,000 village committees and four
million cadres at the end of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Signs Central European Free Trade Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Romania signed the Central
European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) today which will make it the
trade bloc's sixth member when formally admitted on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The CEFTA comprises Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic,
Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was first signed by the Czech Republic, Hungary,
Poland and Slovakia on December 21, 1992, and took effect on
January 1, 1993. Slovenia signed the accord in January 1996 to
become the bloc's fifth member.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea said at the signing
ceremony that admitance to the CEFTA will help promote his
country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The CEFTA provides for tax exemption on imports between member
states of the trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Romania ran a trade volume of 738 million
U.S. dollars with CEFTA members, which accounted for 4.2 percent
of Romania's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Romania's exports to these countries last year was 276 million
dollars, while imports were 462 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
After signing the CEFTA document, Romania will enjoy tax
exemption for 80 percent of imported and exported industrial
products and full exemption by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The CEFTA, viewed as a stepping stone by member states for
joining the wider European Union (EU), has also signed tax-cut
agreement with the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
