<HEADLINE> China Becomes Major Flower Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China has become one of the
world's major flower producers, with an annual output value of
more than 4.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, China planted 75,000 ha in flowers in
1996 and exported 2.58 million kilograms of various kinds of
flowers, earning 130 million US dollars worth of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The country's flower production has been increasing at an
annual rate of 30 percent in recent years. By the end of 1996, it
had over 700 flower markets and more than 100 Sino-foreign joint
flower ventures in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangdong, Fujian, Yunnan,
and other provinces and cities.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu Junfeng, secretary-general of the China Flower
and Plant Association, China is trying to develop annual flower
output to 10 billion yuan by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The official source said that the World Gardening Fair will be
held in Kunming, the capital of south China's Yunnan Province, in
1999.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time for China to host the fair. The
Chinese government has already sent invitations to over 160
countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
