<HEADLINE> Rescue Work for Chinese Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIASHI, Xinjiang, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An all-out effort has
been made in rescue work following a 6.6 magnitude earthquake that
hit Jiashi County of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region at 13:34 Beijing time on Friday, leaving at least nine dead
and causing serious damage.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of cadres and local people of various ethnic groups,
along with 320 officers and men of the armed police of Xinjiang
and 2,000 army soldiers have been mobilized to help restart
production and rebuild homes, according to official sources here.
</P>
<P>
The tremor was the sixth to have hit Jiashi since January 21
that had a magnitude higher than six.
</P>
<P>
In the two townships at the epicenter, almost all houses and
and barns were destroyed and some farmland was flooded. Twenty km
to the northwest, most wooden single-storey houses were destroyed,
and concrete buildings built in recent years, like county
government office buildings, developed cracks.
</P>
<P>
Several hours after the tremor, medical teams were sent to the
area by Kashi Prefecture, the military area command in south
Xinjiang, and by Jiashi County Government. One local farmer told
Xinhua that, "Although the earthquake was serious, we aren't so
frightened that we can't pull ourselves together."
</P>
<P>
The lives of the 280,000 people in the quake area have been
seen to, and victims have been cared for and public order restored.
</P>
<P>
A group led by Tang Quan, deputy director of the State
Seismology Bureau, and a delegation headed by Zhang Wenyue, Vice
Secretary of the Xinjiang regional CPC Committee, arrived in
Jiashi today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
