<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Mainland Is Shifting Eastward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have discovered that
the Chinese mainland has been drifting eastward, having been
affected by the Indian Plate, during a research project headed by
Ye Shuhua, an academic at the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
They used satellite technology, like a global positioning
system, to study crust movement. The east part of China, referring
mainly to Shanghai, was found to be drifting seven to eight
millimeters annually to the east, relative to stable areas on the
European Plate.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai was also found to be moving in a somewhat southerly
direction and to be sinking about a millimeter every year.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that the research shows that China is at a
practical stage and advanced level in the use of space
technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
