<HEADLINE> mee041103hke - Lebanon to Urge for Freeze on Ties with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 12 (Xinhua) - Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz announced here today that he will urge the European and
Mediterranean countries at a Malta gathering to freeze their
relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz left Beirut at noon today, heading a Lebanese delegation
for the conference of the Euro-Mediterranian partnership, a forum
grouping 15 states of the European Union and 12 countries along
the southern Mediterranean basin.
</P>
<P>
The conference is to be held in Valletta, Malta's capital,
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his departure, Boueiz said that he will table the issue of
freezing ties with Israel at the conference unless the Jewish
state respects the principles defined in the 1991 Madrid peace
conference and the formula of exchanging land for peace.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut International Airport, the
lebanese foreign minister stressed that " The resumption of the
peace process should be called for according to the bases of
Madrid and according to the mechanism of the peace process in
Madrid."
</P>
<P>
``We are not ready to enter a new mechanism and to begin to
negotiate once again what has been agreed upon," the Lebanese
official noted.
</P>
<P>
The Malta conference will be the second of the
Euro-Mediterranean partnership, which is aimed at developing
security, political, economic, cultural and social links. The
first of its kind was held in Barcelona, Spain, in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
Europe's Mediterranean partners are Algeria, Cyprus, Egypt,
Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Tunisia, Syria, Turkey
and the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Arab countries decided to freeze the
normalization process with Israel and enforce an Arab boycott of
the Jewish state which infuriated them by starting the
construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
