<HEADLINE> Malaysian Flights Affected by Indian Air Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysia Airlines (MAS)
has decided to cancel all tonight's flights from the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport near here due to "wildcat" strike by Indian
air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference at the airport today, MAS
Managing Director Wan Malik Ibrahim said that the flights canceled
are MH4 (KL-London/Heathrow), MH18 (KL-Zurich-Rome) and MH26
(KL-Dubai-Charles de Gaulle).
</P>
<P>
He said following the cancellation there would be no MAS return
flights on the above routes.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which entered its second day today, also forced MAS
to reschedule five flights Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wan Malik said a MAS flight bound for Kuala Lumpur from Vienna
(MH5) today was diverted to Karachi while that from Munich (MH17)
to Dubai due to the closure of the Indian airspace.
</P>
<P>
Since Friday, he said, the national carrier MAS had been trying
to make alternative arrangements and with the assistance and
cooperation of the Department of Civil Aviation (DCA) and the
International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) had managed to
make arrangement to allow its aircraft to fly through Colombo and
Muscat, in Oman.
</P>
<P>
He said if everything was cleared, all the five flights
rescheduled Friday would be resumed tonight but no time had been
fixed.
</P>
<P>
MAS has deployed about 40 officers to man its reservation
centers at the airport and City office around-the-clock to ensure
the least inconvenience to its passengers.
</P>
<P>
Last night, MAS had to take care of 1,422 stranded passengers,
providing them accommodation at various hotels in the city, meals
and international telephone calls to inform their families of the
situation, he said.  
</P>
