Anabela Sales Ritchie, president of the Macao Legislative
Assembly (LA), made these remarks on the eve of the 10th
anniversary of the signing of the historical document in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The indigenous legislator began her career in the LA in 1976,
and was elected chairman of the assembly twice in 1992 and 1996
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"China and Portugal through the international document designed
the future of the Macao Special Administrative Region," she said.
"I believe that Macao's transition will be a success so long as
the declaration is properly carried out and implemented."
</P>
<P>
The president described the joint declaration, signed in
Beijing on April 13, 1987, as "a model of understanding that
represents peace, equality and good order on the basis of trust
and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
She said that the importance of the joint declaration goes
beyond 1999 after China resumes its exercise of sovereignty over
Macao.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that it is of great significance to the
cultivation in a broader field of bilateral relations between
Portugal and the People's Republic of China," said Ritchie.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of China and Portugal have described their relations as
"excellent." They exchanged visits frequently. The development of
"good, open, frank and constructive relations is a result of the
implementation" of the joint declaration, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The atmosphere of harmony, understanding and mutual respect is
very important to the settlement of existing problems in Macao,"
she said. "The two countries should further expand their relations
by drawing experiences from their cooperation in Macao."
</P>
<P>
She pledged that the Macao LA will take an active part in the
handling of transitional affairs so that a stable transfer of
power will be reached.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
