<HEADLINE> HKSAR Provisional Legislature Ends 4th Meeting in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A bill which provides for
additional holidays this year and general holidays next year was
tabled today to the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) at its fourth full
sitting in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
It is the first bill tabled by the HKSAR Chief Executive's
Office to the council, signifying the start of the PLC's
legislative work after the council's formation last December.
</P>
<P>
The Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill was introduced by Miss Elsie
Leung Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice for the HKSAR, to the PLC for
the first and second readings at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, July 1 and 2 and October 1 this year will be
designated as additional statutory holidays for Hong Kong
residents to celebrate the establishment of the HKSAR and the
National Day of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also adopted the rules of procedure together with
separate amendments made by Maria Tam and Ip Kwok-him to the
draft, after the PLC members' work on it in the past several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the meeting endorsed amendments to the
resolution passed at last meeting on registration of members'
interests, which were moved by Ip, convenor of the administrative
matters working group.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, PLC members elected Ronald Arculli and Henry
Wu chairman and deputy chairman of the PLC's Finance Committee and
named Leong Che-hung, who chairs the existing Legislative
Council's House Committee, and Ip as chairman and deputy chairman
of the House Committee.
</P>
<P>
Both committees comprise all PLC members excluding PLC
President Rita Fan.
</P>
<P>
During lunch time, the working group on administrative matters
had a meeting on subsistence and traveling allowances for staff of
the PLC Secretariat, which is located in Shenzhen before July 1,
as well as provision of Secretariat support to the PLC on and
after July 1.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attracted some 60 local and overseas reporters with
about 20 Hong Kong residents who went a long way to the meeting
venue at Huaxia Art Center for a look at how the PLC operates. PLC
meetings have been opened to the public since the last meeting.
</P>
<P>
The next full sitting of the PLC is scheduled for April 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
