<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Reach Deal on Anti-Cuba Law Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and the
United States reached a deal Friday on a dispute over the
U.S. Helms-Burton Act against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
EU Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan said in a statement that
the deal would allow the EU to suspend a complaint against the
United States that the World Trade Organization in Geneva was to
take up on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deal would help "chart a path toward a longer-term solution
through amendment of the Helms-Burton Act" and allow talks between
the EU and U.S. on the issue of extraterritorial application of
trade laws, said Brittan.
</P>
<P>
He added that the EU reserved the right to continue the case if
no broader agreement is reached in separate negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The EU insisted that the 1996 Helms-Burton Act, which seeks to
punish foreign companies that invest in property confiscated from
Americans after the 1959 revolution in Cuba, has a negative impact
on the economic interests of its member states.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. President Bill Clinton said in Washington that he
has seen no prospect of changing the embargo policy against the
Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
He added that it would be very difficult to persuade him the
change the current U.S. policy toward Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
