<HEADLINE> Chief Minister of Malaysia's Selangor State Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Chief Minister of Malaysia's
Selangor State, Muhammad Muhamad Taib, who faces two charges in
Australia in connection with his attempt to transfer 2.4 million
ringgit (about 0.96 million U.S. dollars) out of Australia, has
resigned, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
His resignation, effective on Monday, was announced by Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad after the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) Supreme Council meeting at the party
headquarters here today.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad, 51, who was appointed Chief Minister of Selangor on
August 14, 1986, also resigned from the posts of Selangor and
Federal Territory UMNO liaison chief and the Selangor and Federal
Territory National Front chairman.
</P>
<P>
"It is his own wish to resign so that any investigation
conducted will not affect UMNO's image and we will only consider
his position in the party after the decision in Brisbane on
whether he is guilty or not," Mahathir said at a news conference
also attended by Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who is UMNO president, said that Muhammad made his
decision after having heard the views of all the Supreme Council
members during a discussion on corruption and abuse of power and
position.
</P>
<P>
He said that Muhammad's position as the UMNO vice president
would be known on Monday when the Selangor Chief Minister issues
an official statement.
</P>
<P>
On whether Muhammad's decision (to resign) reflected his
admission of guilt, Mahathir said: "I don't know whether it is an
admission of guilt. But what he stated is that he does not want to
be linked with UMNO in any of the investigations."
</P>
<P>
Muhammad was detained at the Brisbane International Airport on
December 22 last year when currency equivalent to 1.2 million
Australian dollars was found in his luggage.
</P>
<P>
He was charged in the Brisbane Magistrate's Court with
attempting to transfer the amount in undeclared currency out of
Australia under the Financial Transactions Reports Act, 1988
which carries a maximum fine of 5,000 Australian dollars (about
4,000 U.S. dollars) or a jail term not exceeding two years or both
on conviction.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at the mention of the case yesterday, the
prosecution stated that Muhammad will face an additional charge of
making a false declaration when his case comes up for hearing on
August 19.
</P>
<P>
The additional charge, under the same Act, carries a maximum
fine of 10,000 Australian dollars (about 8,000 U.S. dollars) or a
jail term not exceeding five years or both on conviction.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad recently became the center of controversy including
being subjected to investigations by the Anti Corruption Agency
(ACA) in connection with the cash found on him and his ownership
of properties in Australia reported to be worth millions of
ringgit (Malaysian currency).
</P>
<P>
Muhammad earlier claimed that the cash belonged to his two
brothers for the purchase of property in the Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
The transaction could not proceed because they could not be
present in Australia for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that Muhammad's replacement as the Chief
Minister, the Selangor and Federal Territory Liaison Committee
chief and the Selangor and Federal Territory National Front
chairman would be decided after discussions later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
