<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeks Business Expansion In Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel is seeking more business
opportunities in Vietnam while consolidating its footholds in
major economic powers in the Far East region.
</P>
<P>
Israel Export Institute (IEI) considers Vietnam as one of the
"new emerging economies," believing that the development boom in
that country would attract Israeli companies to establish a
presence there.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted lately by the IEI said that Vietnam is now
starting the process of rehabilitation and rebuilding its
national infrastructure, making large scale investment and more
imports essential.
</P>
<P>
This situation creates opportunities for companies to acquire a
bigger share or even a competitive edge in this infant market, the
survey said.
</P>
<P>
Amir Hayek, general manager of the IEI, said that Israeli
companies could find a place in agriculture and agrotechnology, a
big business estimated at over 180 million U.S. dollars per annum.
</P>
<P>
In the field of telecommunications, Vietnam expects massive
foreign involvements, with some financial problems still
pending. Israeli entrepreneurs are also allowed to get involved in
such infrastructure projects as supplies and management, which is
expected to earn the Jewish state some 300 million dollars per
year.
</P>
<P>
However, the IEI and Israeli Insurance Company against Foreign
Trade Risks, cautioned against get-rich-quick ambitions.
</P>
<P>
They noted that Vietnam is a developing country, its business
infrastructure has not yet matured, and making business there is
quite difficult. The country's lack of foreign currency and
complicated bureaucracy are also negative factors in doing
business, they said.
</P>
<P>
They strongly recommended that Israel's ties with the major
economic powers -- Japan, China and South Korea, be further
cemented so as to minimize the possible business risks at the new
market.
</P>
<P>
diplomatic relations between Israel and Vietnam is at the
ambassadorial level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
