<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Fall of India's Gowda Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A fluid political situation is
expected to continue in India following the fall of the 13-party
United Front (UF) government headed by Deve Gowda, who was voted
out in a confidence motion in Parliament late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The 10-month-old Gowda government appeared doomed from the very
start, as the modern history of India shows that no coalition
government could manage to last long.
</P>
<P>
From July 28, 1979 to May 16, 1996, the country had seen four
coalition governments set up and led by prime ministers Charan
Singh, V.P.Singh, C.Shekhar and A.B. Vajpayee, but none of them
lasted more than one year.
</P>
<P>
The UF came to power on June 1 last year with the support from
the Congress party after no political party could obtain a
majority in parliament and form a government by itself following
the inconclusive April-May general election.
</P>
<P>
In the 543 elected Parliament seats, the Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP), the so-called "communal force" as labeled by other
"secular" parties, got 193 together with its alliance, while the
13-party UF won 188 seats including 11 supporters.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party got only 141 seats. And determined to
prevent the BJP from coming to power at the center, the Congress
offered its support from outside to the UF which then formed a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 months, the Gowda government has won wide
approval for continuing policies of economic reforms pursued by
the previous governments and enhancing friendly relations with its
neighbors. But it has been torn by constant internal strife, which
is hampering the implementation of its promises and policies.
</P>
<P>
The 13 parties with different political persuasions came from
different parts of the country and held different views on various
issues, making it difficult for them to have a unitary stand.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it was not an easy job to be on good terms with
the UF's outside supporter of the Congress party, which has a
different background and is bent on staging a comeback someday and
form a government of its own. The worsening ties between the UF
and the Congress eventually led to the withdrawal of the
Congress's support to the UF on March 30, and the fall of the
Gowda government became almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Political parties are now busy working out new strategies to
tide over the current impasse. Since the majority of parliament
members loathe going to the polls so soon, they will have to find
a way out through a realignment of political parties.
</P>
<P>
The UF and the Congress are reported to have kept constant
contact with each other and the BJP is also busy mustering support
from small regional parties. However, no matter what kind of
realignment may come into being, none is expected to be able to
offer a stable government in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) recovered a bit but was still weak in the absence
of strong interest this week.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index (CI) recovered 1.58 points to end the week
at 1,138.36, the EMAS Index gained 0.11 of a point to 329.40 while
the Second Board Index lost 12.79 points to 595.03 and the
Industrial Index down 3.85 points to 2,139.25.
</P>
<P>
The market opened the week reeling from the bearish mood over
the central bank's lending curbs for the purchase of property and
shares and Wall Street drop over interest rates woes.
</P>
<P>
Property, construction and finance-based counters were badly
hit by the central bank's lending guidelines which were aimed at
ensuring stability in the local economy over the long term.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank's explanation over its measures and Finance
Minister Anwar Ibrahim's call to investors to invest on the basis
of market fundamentals were somewhat soothing enough for a short
rebound on Tuesday and the day after.
</P>
<P>
However, the market was already expected to fall further to
form a better base for subsequent trading and as such, any rebound
was short-lived as selling pressure continued, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of encouraging news, rumors cropped up saying
that some stockbroking houses had run into financial difficulties
due to the default in margin calls, which put a toll on prices.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds were said to be refusing to buy at this stage
while local funds stayed away from the bearish market.
</P>
<P>
The analysts pegged support for the benchmark CI at 1,100 and
resistance at 1,150 points.
</P>
<P>
The analysts considered the week as a "sell-on-rally market"
and would look up at the Wall Street performance for next week's
direction.
</P>
<P>
The mainboard volume was 1.207 billion shares worth 7.008
billion ringgit ( about 2.8032 billion U.S. dollars) from 1.580
billion shares valued at 9.517 billion ringgit (about 3.8068
billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover stood at 203.042 million shares
valued at 2.213 billion ringgit (about 885.2 million U.S. dollars)
against 265.061 million shares worth 3.066 billion ringgit (about
1.2264 billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals amounted 235.994 million shares worth 1.702
billion ringgit (about 680.8 million U.S. dollars) compared with
239.436 million shares valued at 1.683 billion ringgit (about
673.2 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
This week, one counter, property-based Crescendo Corp, made its
debut on the Main Board on Tuesday with a fair premium of 2.00
ringgit (about 80 U.S. cents) over its offer price of 4.00 ringgit
(about 1.6 U.S. dollars). The counter ended the week at 5.45
ringgit (about 2.18 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the week, property-based Damansara and Metroplex and
trading counter O'Connor's Corp were suspended from trading
pending announcements.
</P>
<P>
Aokam Perdana led the 10 most active counters, down 26 sen to
3.48 ringgit, followed by Chase Perdana which fell 1.10 ringgit to
10.50 ringgit, KLIH down 34 sen to 3.58 ringgit and AMMB-BR which
lost seven sen to 0.24 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
In terms of volume, Aokam Perdana accounted for 45.626 million
shares traded, Chase Perdana 37.493 million shares traded, AMMB-LR
36.080 million shares, KLIH 33.163 million shares, AMMB-BR 31.907
million shares, Renong 28.095 million shares, Sinora 26.457
million shares, Tekala 26.167 million shares, Berjaya Industrial
23.159 million shares and Sime Darby 21.747 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 86.336 million shares traded,
industrial products 242.805 million shares, construction 104.469
million shares, trading/services 162.435 million shares,
infrastructure 2.956 million shares, finance 156.960 million
shares, hotels 45.867 million shares, properties 189.287 million
shares, plantation 30.632 million shares, mining 10.716 million
shares, trusts 2.214 million shares and loan stocks 172.994
million shares.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE is expected to see further dips next week as players
liquidate their stocks to cut losses in the absence of strong
interest this week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
