<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the CPO physicals market was on the uptrend,
opening the week at 1,287.50 ringgit (about 515 U.S. dollars) per
ton and ending at 1,305 ringgit (about 522 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
April South closed the week at 1,305 ringgit (about 522 U.S.
dollars) per ton, up 15 ringgit (about six U.S. dollars) against
last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Private crop forecaster Ivan Wong's bearish forecast released
on Monday somewhat stagnated the market. Wong estimated a 32
percent increase for March production and exports for the same
month at 560,000 tons compared with 377,000 tons for February.
</P>
<P>
He also forecast that March stocks would rise slightly to
725,000 tons from 723,000 tons in February.
</P>
<P>
Higher export forecast by cargo surveyor Caleb Brett for the
first 10 days of April aided the bullish market. Caleb Brett's
export forecast was at 204,00 tons compared with 161,000 tons for
the first 10 days of March.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that emergence of strong leads are expected to
further push up the price of CPO physicals next week.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to receive a bullish export forecast for
the first 15 days of April by cargo surveyor Societe Generale de
Surveillance and this would continue the market's uptrend, they
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the price of the metal
was volatile this week.
</P>
<P>
It opened the week at 14.27 ringgit (about 5.708 U.S. dollars)
per kg but was lower the next day at 14.18 ringgit (about 5.672
U.S. dollars) per kg. It moved up slightly the following day, and
was again in the downtrend for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
It closed the week at 14.10 ringgit (about 5.64 U.S. dollars)
per kg, lower by 19 sen from last week's close at 14.29 ringgit
(about 5.716 U.S. dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The turnover this week increased to 449 tons from 370 tons last
week with the locals, European and Japanese players dominating the
transactions.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is expected to experience volatile trading next week
with the price likely to hover between 14.05 ringgit (about 5.62
U.S. dollars) and 14.25 ringgit (about 5.7 U.S. dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
However, the metal, which is traded in U.S. dollars on the
London Metal Exchange, is expected to gain support from the strong
greenback following the U.S. government's policy to maintain the
strong parity of its currency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Malaysian rubber market was very quiet
throughout the week due to weak Indonesian prices and bearish
regional markets.
</P>
<P>
There were no strong leads in the market during the week to
push up rubber prices and this resulted in a gradual slide of the
prices.
</P>
<P>
RSS One and SMR 20 fell to 290.50 sen (about 116.2 U.S. cents)
per kg and 275 sen (about 110 U.S. cents) per kg respectively at
the week's close from 294.50 sen (about 117.8 U.S. cents) per kg
and 278.50 sen (about 111.4 U.S. cents) per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian rubber prices are expected to continue their
downtrend next week unless strong leads emerge to support the
market, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said the market hoped to see a rebound in Indonesian
rubber prices so that they could spill over the bullish sentiment
to the local front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
