<HEADLINE> LRA Headquaters Overrun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) overran the headquaters of the Lord's Resistance Army in
southern Sudan, killing 153 people and captured 210 Ugandan
rebels, "the New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kony, the main leader of LRA, had fled to southern
Sudanese city of Juba, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The LRA's headquaters in Aru and camps in Pingiri were heavily
guarded by the government troops of Sudan. The dead include the
government soldiers of Sudan and Ugandan rebels and some Arabs,
SPLA sources said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Five tanks, one Katyusha rocket and dozens of guns were
captured by SPLA in the battle on April 9 and 10, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
A source of Uganda army said they did not know the battle yet.
</P>
<P>
LRA has three detachments of some 200 soldiers each, an
earlier report said. Recent reports said that LRA sent three
batches of its fighters to northern Uganda, but the number of the
three batches could not to be determined. Another recent report
said that a group of some 100 LRA rebels was being pursued by the
government troops in the north.
</P>
<P>
LRA is one of the three main rebel groups in Uganda. The other
two are the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) which was active in
north-western Uganda and the main forces of which is annihilated
by SPLA in southern Sudan last month, and the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF) active in the west which lost its main forces in its
battle against the government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
