<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese LDP Guideline on Foreign Policy Toward Asia-Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) Friday put forward its guideline on foreign policy
towards the Asia-Pacific region, stressing the maintaining and
strengthening of the Japan-U.S. security framework.
</P>
<P>
The guideline, which has been drawn up since 1994 by the LDP
and was approved Friday, would serve as the basic principles of
the party's foreign policy, said media reports.
</P>
<P>
Under the guideline, Japan will continue to strengthen its
alliance with the United States and also establish multilateral
security safeguard.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the Japan-U.S. alliance with the security
system at the core would be "the most important topic" of Japan's
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
It said that multilateral dialogues on security should be held
so as to set up multilateral security system in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
The guideline suggested that Japan, the United States and China
hold a three-nation summit, establish a security mechanism in
Northeastern Asia with themselves at the center, and conduct
regular defense ministers' meetings.
</P>
<P>
The LDP proposed that Japan should reevaluate its cooperative
policy toward China, including its loans to China in Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
It said Japan should suggest that China and Russia attend the
G-7 summit in the future.
</P>
<P>
The LDP's foreign policy guideline also proposed the
establishment of a free trade system as well as Japan's active
cooperation with other regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0145 </DOCNO>
