<HEADLINE> Germany Releases More Loan to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany has released a loan of
31.5 million U.S. dollars to Uganda for further financial
assistance to the east African country, reported the local daily
"the New vision" today.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the loan was signed here yesterday by Ugandan
minister of state for finance Mathew Rukikaire and the German
ambassador to Uganda Hans Joachim on behalf of their respective
governments.
</P>
<P>
Rukikaire said out of the loan, 8.2 m dollars will be used for
the water supply and sanitation project for Kabale town near
Rwanda, 6 m dollaars for roads program phase iv for eastern
Uganda and 2.5 m dollars for re-integration of demobilsed
soldiers (phase ii).
</P>
<P>
The other money is to be used in other projects such as Uganda
railways container terminal in Kampala and vocational training
centres for the ministry of labour among others.
</P>
<P>
Rukikaire praised the close cooperation between the two
countries, while Joachim promised to maintain it and stressed the
confidence his government has in the stability and development in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the two countries has developed fast in
recent years. Germany held intergovernmental development policy
talks with Uganda in Bonn last October and decided to give Uganda
a loan of 77 m dm (about 46.2 m U.S. dollars) for financial
assistance to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
