<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Ranks First in Teenage Pregnancies in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three percent of Uganda
teenagers are mothers or pregnant with their first child, making
the country lead in teenage pregnancies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Francois Farah, the United Nations population fund
reporesentative in Uganda was quoted by today's local daily "the
New Vision" today as saying that adolescents here engage in
sexual relations at an early age is the reason of the high
percentage of pregnancies among teenages.
</P>
<P>
He said this is partly due to lack of information about its
consequences and for lack of guidance.
</P>
<P>
He said girls are often too shy to discuss reproductive health
issues with their mothers who are also too shy to discuss sex
with their daughters.
</P>
<P>
He said traditional initiation through aunties is fading away
when there is no modern substitute to assist the youth in growing
up.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Farah said girls often lack information on how to
protect themselves against pregnancies and yet they are expected
never to say no to sexual advances from boys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
