<HEADLINE> Russia Plans Military Pullout From Moldova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said today Russia was planning to pull out its
5,000-strong troops from the east bank of the Dniestr River in
Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Primakov was speaking at a news conference in the Moldovan
capital Kishinev after taking part in talks between Moldovan
government leaders and separatists at the east bank, known as
Transdniestria.
</P>
<P>
But the Russian minister didn't disclose the date of pullout.
</P>
<P>
The Russian troops entered Moldova in 1992 to halt a civil war
between the government and the separatists, who refused to be part
of Macedonia after the mainly Romanian-speaking nation became
independent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the two sides have agreed to sign a "memorandum
of understanding on normalizing relations between Moldova and
Transdniestria" before May 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
A new article would be added into the memorandum, making clear
that Moldova and Transdniestria "will develop their relations as
part of a single state," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moldovan President Petru Lucinschi initially refused to sign
the document when it was drawn up last June, saying that it
breached "the principle of the intangibility of borders."
</P>
<P>
A Moldovan government spokesman told Xinhua in a telephone
interview that Moldova was satisfied with the Russian promise for
troop withdrawal and the separatist leaders' recognition of
Transdniestria as part of Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Primakov visited Kishinev for a day to discuss the relations
between Russia and Moldova, and to mediate between the Moldovan
government and the separatists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
