the current 46,000 soldiers to 34,000 by September 1.
</P>
<P>
After the restructuring, Shpak told the Interfax news agency,
the Russian paratroops will be left with three divisions, a
special regiment and two teaching centers.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1,000 officers will be decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Rodionov has outlined to cut
200,000 men from the armed forces in 1997, as part of a plan to
downsize the military from 1.5 million to 1.2 million by 1998.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to cost Russia some two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin sacked former paratroops commander
Yevgeny Podkolzin and his deputy Vladimir Kazantsev last October
for their opposition against the government's downsizing plan.
