<HEADLINE> Envoy Says Force in Albania to Secure Aid, Restore Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The major goal of a multinational
protection force to be deployed in Albania is to guard aid
deliveries and help restore public order, not to disarm locals,
chief European mediator for Albania said today.
</P>
<P>
Franz Vranitzky, former Austrian chancellor and now chief of
international coordination effort, said the force had no mandate
to disarm locals, but Albanians would be encouraged to surrender
their weapons seized from state armories when they saw the
situation was safer.
</P>
<P>
"The most important task is to protect humanitarian and
economic aid and ensure that it does not get into the hands of
illegitimate groups," he said.
</P>
<P>
Italian advance units of the multinational force arrived in
Albania on Friday and the bulk of the force is due to begin
deployment next Monday in the tiny Balkan nation, where violence
erupted following the collapse of a number of shady pyramid
investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky, working on behalf of the 54-nation Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), said the OSCE's major
aims included: supporting the caretaker government; resoring
public order; furthering dialogue and cooperation; delivering aid
and working to allow elections be held in June.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky said that the goals could not be fulfilled
individually. "All of these activities are dependent on one
another. The holding of these elections will not be possible in
chaos and anarchy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vranitzky said he would travel to Tirana next Wednesday with
Austrian diplomat Herbert Grubmayr to prepare the ground for an
OSCE mission.
</P>
<P>
Grubmayr was newly appointed by the OSCE to coordinate a
three-pronged international relief effort -- comprising the OSCE,
the European Union and the multinational force -- in Albania.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people have been killed since rebels took control
of the country's south last month in an eruption of anger
following the collapse of the saving schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
