<HEADLINE> Mongolian Economy Further Down in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's national economy in
the first quarter of the year slipped further on the downward
trend that started in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, according to a State Statistics Bureau report
released on Friday, the government recorded a budget deficit of
5.8 billion togrog (about seven million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The quarterly deficit was stemmed from the government's total
spenditures of 48.1 billion togrog (58.2 million dollars) and its
revenues of 42.3 billion togrog (51.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the country's industrial sector, output in the first three
months of the year stood at 44.1 billion togrog (53.4 million
dollars), 4.8 percent less than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in animal husbandry, Mongolia's single most
important agricultural sector, a 98.3 percent survival rate
brought alive more than 3.4 million newborn livestock animals.
</P>
<P>
However, as the survival rate for newborns was about the same
as previous years, the number of adult animals dropped by 235,800,
a further down of 183,300 compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The price index in March, if calculated on the basis of the
fixed price in 1995, went up by 8.1 percent against last December
and 2.3 percent compared with February.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly increase of the price index in the first
quarter was 2.7 percent, said the government report.
</P>
<P>
On the labor market, 60,800 people -- 5.12 percent of
Mongolia's labor force -- were registered as jobless by April 1,
or 5,364 more than the total at the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
