<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Thailand Begins Songkran Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Today is the start of the annual
Songkran Festival Holiday, which signifies the beginning of the
Thai new year.
</P>
<P>
For the Thais, it is the time of family togetherness and joy
and revelry.
</P>
<P>
Officially, the three-day Songkran holiday begins on Sunday,
and plus a two-day weekend, the holiday lasts five days, until
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, many workers will not be back to work until April 21,
making it a nine-day holiday.
</P>
<P>
Starting on Friday afternoon, there has been a massive exodus
from Bangkok and its environs to the upcountry, with migrant
workers leaving for home in the north and northeast to join their
families for the annual festivities.
</P>
<P>
Others leave for seaside resorts or make overseas trips.
</P>
<P>
Airlines, trains and long-distance buses have all increased
their services to cope with the upsurge in the number of
holiday-makers.
</P>
<P>
The main feature of the festival is water pouring, in
particular by and among children and youngsters, who douse each
other and passers-by with buckets of water to cool them down and
have a good laugh.
</P>
<P>
The temperature at Songkran usually rises to its zenith, at
about 40 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
After the Songkran Festival, the rainy season starts and
farmers get ready to plough the fields for the rice-planting.
</P>
<P>
Rice is the most important food crop grown in all regions of
Thailand. Over 50 percent of the Thai farmland is planted to rice,
yielding about 20 million tons of paddy annually.
</P>
<P>
Thailand exports rice to more than 100 countries and regions
and takes the lead in the world market, sharing 40 percent of the
volume.
</P>
<P>
The second day of the festival is devoted to respect for the
elderly. Young people and children gently pour water over the
hands of the aged, their parents and grandparents, wishing them a
happy and long life, while the elderly wish the younger generation
a successful career.
</P>
<P>
At public places and temples, beauty, costume, fruit, animal
and cultural performance contests and religious rites are held.
</P>
<P>
On April 20, Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh is scheduled
to preside over the opening of the Songkran procession as well as
the Miss Songkran Beauty Contest at Pradaeng, in the southern part
of Bangkok.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year Loan for Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a three-year loan of some 75 million
U.S. dollars to support Macedonia's economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The loan, channeled through the IMF's Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF), is provided to back the 1997-99
economic reform program of the former Yugoslav Republic.
</P>
<P>
The first annual loan, equivalent to about 25 million dollars,
will be made available in two equal semiannual installments, the
first of which is available immediately.
</P>
<P>
Under the medium term, the program targets annual gross
domestic product (GDP) growth of about 5 percent, inflation of 2
to 3 percent yearly, and a decline in the external current account
deficit to 5.3 percent of GDP from 12 percent of GDP in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In this context of the strategy, the program for 1997 aims for
real GDP growth of 5 percent, year-end inflation of 2 percent, and
an external current account deficit of 8.5 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia succeeded to the membership in the IMF of the former
Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia from December 14, 1992.
Its quota is about 68 million dollars and its outstanding use of
IMF credit stands at about 64 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting eligible
member nations that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico-Northern Triangle Free Trade Talks to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations for a free trade
agreement between Mexico and the Central America's Northern
Triangle countries, namely, Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador,
will continue in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, from April 28 to 30.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Nunez, vice minister of the Honduran Foreign Trade
Ministry, said today in a report received from Tegucigalpa that
the meeting of negotiators-in-chiefs will try to reach consensus
on some points of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Although the four countries have reached consensus on about 80
percent of the trade agreement, "there are still sensitive points
in the hands of the negotiators, who must find formulas to open
consensus options among the parts," Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
In two or three months, Nunez said, the representatives of the
four countries will hold dialogues to decide what products will be
covered by the agreement and the issues concerning tariff
elimination among the four countries.
</P>
<P>
Nunez said the agreement would be ready by the end of the year,
as negotiations have been advancing as planned since they were
restarted in 1996 at the request of the presidents of the four
countries.
</P>
<P>
Issues already discussed include tariff reduction for
agricultural and industrial products, sanitary and technical
standards, unfair trade practices, trade protectionism, solution
of controversies, investments, and government purchases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
