<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Wants Embassy Assailant Extradited From Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica has requested the
extradition from Nicaragua of the leader of Commando Yolaina who
stormed the Nicaraguan embassy in San Jose in 1993, Nicaraguan
Ministry of Foreign Affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
"The request has been acknowledged. But it will be decided by
the Supreme Court of Justice of our country according to our
constitution," said David Silva, spokesman of Nicaraguan Ministry
of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Urbina Lara and two masked men, who made up the
so-called Commando Yolaina, stormed the Nicaraguan embassy in San
Jose on March 8, 1993, and took 20 embassy staff members,
including the ambassador, hostage.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican authorities said the extradition request for Urbina
Lara was presented by the Costa Rican Supreme Court of Justice to
its Nicaraguan counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Urbina Lara was arrested on January 31 when he returned to
Nicaragua. The other two members of the Yolaina commando have not
been identified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
