<HEADLINE> Dutch PM: Special EU Summit Likely on May 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands, now holding the
rotating presidency of the European Union (EU), is likely to call
a special EU summit to pave ways for a revised Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The EU presidency is considering such a summit meeting to take
place on May 23, Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok was quoted by Dutch
radio monitored here as saying today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
However, no decision has been made so far, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo told EU
foreign ministers gathering in the Dutch town of Noordwijk that
the possibility for a special summit in May was "increasing."
</P>
<P>
Dutch officials indicate that whether there will be a special
summit depends on the progress made in the negotiations on a
revised Maastricht Treaty setting economic benchmarks for EU
countries to join the European Monetary Union in 1999.
</P>
<P>
EU sources say that a final decision on the summit is expected
to be hammered out when foreign ministers of the 15-nation bloc
meet in Luxembourg later this month.
</P>
<P>
The date of May 23 is less than one month before EU heads of
government meet in Amsterdam, capital of the Netherlands, to
approve the new treaty.
</P>
<P>
Dutch officials have intended to avoid holding two summits
close together this summer, but they now see it as essential if an
agreement is to be reached in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
