<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican exports to Asia reached 22.91 million
U.S. dollars during the first two months of the year, a 52.5
percent rise over the same period last year, according to Foreign
Trade Ministry statistics.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine exports in January and February of
1997 reached a record high of 3.707 billion dollars, a 29 percent
increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the two-month period added up to 4.313 billion
dollars, 32 percent over the same period of 1996, and resulted in
a deficit of 606 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Motor vehicle sales in Colombia dropped by
2.5 percent in March with 10,046 units sold, against 10,297 sold
during the same month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's non-traditional exports value during the
first quarter of the year reached 661 million dollars, an 11
percent rise over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the Industry and Commerce Ministry show
that private sector took up 74.1 percent of the total exports with
505 million dollars, while those of the public sector took 156
million dollars, 25.9 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- A total of 6,489 new motor vehicles were sold
during the first quarter of this year in Uruguay, a 18 percent
rise over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to data provided by dealers, the sales increase took
place largely with Volkswagen, Chevrolet, Renault, Citroen and
Mitsubishi, although Fiat still was the biggest seller with a 16
percent market share. 
</P>
</TEXT>
