<HEADLINE> Thai Researchers Find New Way to Detect Sick Shrimps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from the
Bangkok-based Mahidol University have discovered a new method to
detect viruses in shrimps, which could help curb those diseases
threatening Thailand's shrimp exports.
</P>
<P>
The researchers from the faculty of science of the University
found that the technique of polymerase chain reaction can
accurately identify viruses when they are still in early stage in
baby shrimps within one day.
</P>
<P>
To detect the viruses that could cause shrimp diseases, like
"yellow head", and "white spots", sample baby shrimps should be
kept in 70 percent alcohol, according to the researchers.
</P>
<P>
The fatality rate of shrimps contracting these diseases could
be as high as 80 percent, they said, adding that the technique
will benefit shrimp farmers and exporters.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that Thailand's shrimp exports dropped to
43 billion baht (1.72 billion US dollars) in 1996 from 52 billion
baht (2.08 billion dollars) and the epidemics of the two diseases
was one of the major factors contributing to the decrease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
