<HEADLINE> Number of Thailand's Mental Illness Patients Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- About 600,000 people, or one in a
hundred persons in Thailand, are suffering from mental illness or
psychosis and the number is on the rise, according to a senior
Public Health Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Preecha Intho, director general of the Mental Health
Department, based his judgment on figures during the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
He said looser family relationships, as a result of social and
economic changes in the country, are responsible for the increase
in the number of mental patients.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed tough competition in society to the
increase.
</P>
<P>
He said that when suffering from mental illness, young adults
turn unusually aggressive, while the elderly and children become
abnormally passive.
</P>
<P>
He added that hot weather is not a major cause of mental
illness or psychosis as many believe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
