<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Catch Rainwater For Better Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- When Luo Youshun, a farmer in
Luoma Village of Huining County, Gansu Province, entertains a
guest, he fetches a basin of hot water so his visitor can wash,
then offers him tea.
</P>
<P>
Luo says this practice is unusual: most villagers would rather
serve their guests steamed buns than a cup of tea, and the guests
clean up with a towel dipped in a mug of water. Just a few years
ago water was more precious than food oil in the eyes of farmers
here, he says.
</P>
<P>
Now, the farmers in northwest China's dry mountainous areas
have bettered their lot by catching rainwater.
</P>
<P>
Luo's village, like most of the province's high arid areas, is
short of groundwater and has no rivers. Farmers rely heavily on
rainfall, which they store in wells. But collecting a sufficient
water supply is difficult because of the highly absorbent soil.
</P>
<P>
In dry years, farmers traveled 15 km to fetch bitter and salty
fountain water, Luo says. In 1995, the well dried up and the local
government had to send for water from the Yellow River irrigation
areas a long distance away.
</P>
<P>
He attributes the village's water supply turnaround to a
government-sponsored rainfall storage project, which has
benefitted 250,000 households and uplifted the appearance of
farmers' courtyards, now noteably more sanitary and planted with
flowers, vegetables and trees. Earthen roofs are covered with tile
and courtyards lined with cement to create the best water flow
into the storage wells.
</P>
<P>
Luo's once-muddy yard was littered with farm tools. He's
cleaned it up, and no longer feeds poultry and livestock in the
yard for safe water's sake. He says he is careful now not to leave
cigarette butts on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Some villagers have installed hand pumps on their new
wells. Others store rainwater in an elevated container, which is
connected with pipes that run into their kitchens, providing
running water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hits Record in Grain Purchasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- China hit a record to purchase
118.5 billion kg of grain during the first three months this year,
24.1 billion kg more than the same period in 1996, today's
Beijing-based "People's Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Greater effort has enabled the country to purchase nearly all
of the grain that the farmers want to put on sales, further
encouraging their initiatives for farming and enhancing the
country's ability in macro-control of grain purchasing.
</P>
<P>
The bumper harvest of 1996 encouraged the country to take a
series of measures, such as adding the volume of special grain
reserves, to expand its capability to purchase grain.
</P>
<P>
The country's various provinces, regions and municipalities
have set new purchasing prices expected to offer more benefits for
the farmers.
</P>
<P>
By last month northeast China's Heilongjiang, Jilin and
Liaoning provinces and north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region had kept a large stock of grain totalling 63.1 billion kg,
rising 77 percent over the same period in 1996. The three
provinces and the region had transported five billion kg of grain
to some middle and big cities and areas short of grain supply by
March. The figure is expected to rise to 8.7 billion kg by the
coming June. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
