<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Telkom to Speed up Vote Counting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's state-owned
telecommunications company Pt. Telkom and the General Election
Institute (LPU) have agreed to use Telkomnet service to speed up
vote counting in the upcoming general election scheduled for May
29.
</P>
<P>
"The network will count votes faster than the method used in
the 1992 general election,' Pt. Telkom operation director Dadad
Kustiwa said here last night after opening a Telkomnet exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The facility, called Telkomnet, will link 40 cities in the
country with a digital data communications system, the director
said.
</P>
<P>
The Telkomnet will need 2.1 billion rupiah (about 913,000 US
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992 election, it took the committee three days to
count all the votes from all polling places throughout the
country. For the coming election, it will take only one day to do
the task, Kustiwa added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's three political parties -- the ruling party Golkar,
the United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian Democratic
Party (PDI) are preparing for the May 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
The three parties are vying for 425 seats of the house of
representatives in the election during which more than 120 million
people are eligible to vote.  
</P>
</TEXT>
