<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Starts Anti-Corruption Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
signed today an anti-corruption program in a fresh effort to pull
the country out of the deep-rooted crime.
</P>
<P>
The program, said Justice Minister Sergy Holovaty, is to check
on all public servants before October 1, and fire those found to
be related to corruption or criminal groups.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a review on how all senior government officials
implement the nation's Anti-Corruption Law should be accomplished
before August 1, 1998, Holovaty told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's Anti-Corruption Law, adopted in October 1995, so far
has shown no teeth. Some international organizations, including
the World Bank, have already expressed concern about the situation.
</P>
<P>
World Bank President James Wolfensohn, who complained about
corruption in a letter to Kuchma last year, raised the issue again
when he met the Ukrainian president in February at the World
Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma then kicked off a "Clean Hands" campaign against graft
immediately after returning to Kiev. The 13-page program signed
today is the first production of Kuchma's anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
However, doubts remain over how much the program can achieve.
Since 1991, only 3,000 people have been punished for job-related
crimes, but none of them held a top-level position in government,
according to statistics from the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Holovaty said in March that the main base of corruption is the
officials who are now running the government and who will also see
to Kuchma's anti-corruption program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
