<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (17-18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (17-18)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: After China resumes its exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, can the National People's Congress (NPC) enact laws for
Hong Kong?
</P>
<P>
Answer: No, the NPC cannot unilaterally enact laws on Hong
Kong's internal administrative affairs. That is because the Basic
Law stipulates that the Hong Kong SAR has legislative power. The
Legislature of Hong Kong is the Legislative Council of the Hong
Kong SAR which will enact laws in accordance with procedures as
prescribed by the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Laws enacted by the legislature of the Hong Kong SAR must be
reported to the NPC Standing Committee for record. The process of
reporting does not affect the entry into force of such laws.
</P>
<P>
Should the NPC Standing Committee, after consulting Committee
for the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR that operates under it,
finds that any law enacted by the Hong Kong legislature does not
conform to provisions of the Basic Law regarding affairs within
the responsibility of the central authorities as well as the
relationship between the central government and the Hong Kong SAR,
it may return the law in question but will not amend it. Any law
returned by the NPC Standing Committee will immediately be
invalidated. Such invalidation will have no retroactive power
unless otherwise provided for in laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Question: Can people in the mainland freely enter Hong Kong
after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Some people in the mainland think that, after July 1,
1997, they may freely go to Hong Kong. This is a misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is too small a place to have a big
population. Despite being a free port, therefore, Hong Kong has
always exercised entry controls to prevent its population from
exploding. Before 1997, there has been a strict restriction on the
number of mainlanders allowed to settle in Hong Kong. The same
strict restriction will be imposed in this regard after 1997. Also
mainlanders will not be as free to visit Hong Kong as they are to
travel from one place to another in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that, to enter the Hong Kong SAR,
people from other parts of China must apply for approval and that
the number of mainlanders allowed to enter the SAR for settlement
be determined by competent authorities of the central government
after consulting the Hong Kong regional government. After 1997,
therefore, there will be continued restrictions on the number of
mainlanders entering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that, after China resumes its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, many mainlanders will want to visit
the region, relevant departments will, in a planned way, increase
the number of tour groups for Hong Kong to be organized by travel
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
