<HEADLINE> FIFA to Investigate Roethlisberger Case, Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 11 (Xinhua) -- World soccer ruling body FIFA said
they would investigate Swiss referee Kurt Roethlisberger who on
Thursday lost his appeal to UEFA against a life ban for attempted
bribery, according to reports reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In another development, European governing body UEFA said on
Friday it was planning to look into another match-fixing
allegation, involving Roethlisberger and Bayern Munich, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Roethlisberger was suspended by UEFA after they found he
solicited a bribe to fix a European Cup Champions' League match
between Grasshopper Zurich and Auxerre on October 30.
</P>
<P>
But the ban extends only to UEFA-related activities and does
not apply worldwide. UEFA plans to forward the findings of their
investigation to FIFA who will examine the case, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said in a statement Roethlisberger could face a worldwide
ban if their findings concurred with those of UEFA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
