<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Currency Deposit Accounts Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign currency deposit (FCDU)
accounts in the Philippines' commercial banking system hit another
record high of 15.6 billion U.S. dollars for the first quarter
this year, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures released Thursday by the central bank, the
reports said that the FCDU level as of March 31 represents a 743
million dollars increase from the end-February level of 14.8
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest FCDU level also represents a 5.37 billion dollars
increase from the year-ago level of 10.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although not officially counted as part of the country's gross
international reserves, the FCDU deposits are nonetheless
considered as a second layer of Philippine international reserves.
</P>
<P>
FCDU accounts are mostly U.S. dollar accounts kept by families
of overseas contract workers, export-oriented firms, and companies
receiving foreign investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
