<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Send 51 Athletes to East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will send 51 athletes
to the Second East Asian Games slated for May 10-19 in Pusan,
South Korea, it was announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Pusan Games will be the last comprehensive sporting event
Hong Kong athletes are to participate before the handover at the
midnight on June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
From July 1 on, Hong Kong will be part of China, under the name
of Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), and its athletes
will compete in international events under the name of "Hong
Kong, China", as stipulated by the Basic Law concerning the SAR.
</P>
<P>
In Pusan, Hong Kong athletes will compete in six medal sports,
namely athletics, gymnastics, badminton, judo, swimming and
diving, and Wushu and demonstration events of rowing and bowling.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong athletes collected one gold, two silver and eight
bronze medals at the inaugural East Asian Games in Shanghai in
1993.
</P>
<P>
But it would be harder now than four years ago for Hong Kong to
do equally well in terms of number of medals, as two of the sports
in which Hong Kong competed in Shanghai had been put as
demonstration events.
</P>
<P>
"Anyway, we hope that our athletes could do ever better at
Pusan," said Pang Chung, Chef de Mission of the Hong Kong
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The first group of Hong Kong athletes and officials are
scheduled to leave for South Korea on May 7, Pang said. 
</P>
