<HEADLINE> US, EU Reach Agreement on Anti-Cuba Law Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
the United States today reached an agreement on a dispute over the
Helms-Burton Act against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the deal, U.S. Commerce Undersecretary Stuart
Eizenstat said the U.S. and EU promised "best efforts" to develop
a broader agreement by October 15.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels earlier today, EU announced that it will suspend a
complaint against the U.S. to the World Trade Organization (WTO),
but it could be revived if no broader agreement is reached in
separate negotiations.
</P>
<P>
EU Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan emphasized that EU
reserves its right to refile the complaint before the WTO if there
is no final solution.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, reached after intensive telephone
contacts between trade officials of both sides, the Clinton
administration will persuade U.S. Congress to abandon some
provisions of the law.
</P>
<P>
EU insisted that the law, which aims to stop foreign trade in
Cuba, is a violation of the free trade principles of WTO.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. argued that the complaint by EU has interfered in
its foreign policy, saying WTO has no right to make a verdict on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement avoids placing our foreign policy interests
before the WTO, an organization designed to facilitate trade, not
arbitrate foreign policy disputes," Eizenstat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
