<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves $657 Mln Stand-By Credit for Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved credits totaling some 657 million U.S.
dollars equivalent for Bulgaria in an effort to back its
government's economic programs.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, about 147 million dollars equivalent is available
under the cereal element of the Compensatory and Contingency
Financing Facility (CCFF), which provides financing to member
nations experiencing balance of payments problems caused by an
excess in the cost of their cereal imports that is both temporary
and beyond the control of the authorities. A further some 510
million dollars is available over the next 14 months under a
stand-by credit to bolster the government's economic program for
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The program is targeted to limit the decline of real GDP to 4.8
percent in 1997, as growth turns positive by mid-year, reduce
monthly inflation to 2 percent by the end of the year, maintain a
small surplus in the current account and double official reserves
to the equivalent of three months of imports of goods and
nonfinancial services.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria joined the IMF in September, 1990. Its quota is about
637 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit currently
totals about 520 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IMF okayed a 20-month stand-by credit on July 19, last
year, equivalent to about 548 million dollars, of which Bulgaria
drew only about 110 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
