<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge on Inflation Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 11 (Xinhua) -- New inflation worries fanned up
by March economic data sent the Dow Jones industrial average down
nearly 150 points today and erased all of 1997's gains.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 148.36 points to
6,391.69, down 134.38 for the week.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market measures also posted stiff losses after the bond
market slid, boosting interest rates to a nine-month high,
following this morning's reports on wholesale prices and retail
sales.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 444.36 million
shares a bit more than 426.35 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 20.69 to 737.65, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 9.85 to 389.51.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index dropped 28.87 to 1,206.90, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 7.03 to 556.16.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which just a month ago was sporting a gain of nearly
10 percent on the year, is now down almost 1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that wholesale prices, excluding
food and energy, shot up unexpectedly. The so-called core rate
rose 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department, meanwhile, reported a modest 0.2
percent increase in retail sales for March, but nearly doubled its
initial estimate of February's consumer activity to a 1.5 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
As bonds fell, the yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond rose to
about 7.16 percent, its highest point since July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
