<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Help from Congress in Trade, Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today called on the Congress to ratify the Chemical Weapons
Convention and to give him fast-track authority he needs to expand
trade with Latin Americans.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks here before a luncheon of the American
Society of Newspaper Editors.
</P>
<P>
Citing the fact that Latin American nations had more trade with
Europe than the U.S. last year, Clinton said,"There is no reason
to think other nations will wait while we sit idle."
</P>
<P>
Saying that every president since 1974 has had the authority to
negotiate trade agreements under procedures requiring Congress to
accept or reject them without amendments, Clinton asked for the
same power.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's "fast-track" authority expired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has sought to bring Chile into the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) which groups the U.S.,
Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The so-called fast-track authority would give Clinton the power
to conclude an agreement with Chile that Congress would have to
vote for or against without delay by making amendments.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't seize these opportunities, our competitors
surely will," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged the Senate to do "what is right" and ratify
the Chemical Weapons Convention before the treaty goes into effect
on April 29.
</P>
<P>
"If we fail to do it...we won't be there to enforce a treaty
that we have helped to write, leaving our military and our people
more vulnerable to a silent and sudden killer," he said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which has been signed by 161 countries and ratified
by 70 of them, bans development, production, stockpiling and use
of all chemical warfare agents and requires they be destroyed
within 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Opponents led by Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee insisted that the treaty does not serve the
interests of the U.S. and are opposed to the ratification before
amendments to the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
