<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Racial Suit against Agriculture Department Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- A southern Virginia farmer has
become the first of a group of black farmers to settle one of a
racial discrimination complaints against the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
Willie L. Chute, 38, had filed an administrative complaint
charging USDA officials with delaying his loan application because
of his race.
</P>
<P>
Chute's attorney said the case was settled on Thursday and
Chute received a "substantial payment" from the department.
</P>
<P>
The settlement was confirmed on Friday by Tom Amontree, press
secretary for Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
In February Glickman announced his intention to eliminate
within 120 days a longstanding backlog of 875 discrimination
complaints involving farm loan programs.
</P>
<P>
Chute had sought a 119,000-dollar USDA loan in 1993 to build a
poultry house to raise chickens under contract with a major
poultry business.
</P>
<P>
His application was approved but far too late to win the
contract. Federal officials upheld his complaint that the loan was
delayed for a year because he was black.
</P>
<P>
USDA investigators found that white farmers in Chute's county
typically waited 84 days for loan decisions, while black farmers
had to wait an average of 222 days. They also found that 84
percent of white farmers had their applications approved compared
to only 56 percent of blacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
