<DOCNO> XIE19970412.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Palestinians Renounce Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leaders have made
a clear statement to remain committed to thwarting terrorism, the
U.S. State Department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters that
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright held a meeting with a
visiting Palestinian delegation last night, and "she received very
clear, very specific assurances from the delegation that the
Palestinians remain fundamentally committed to thwarting
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Palestinian Authority had took measures
against extremists by helping Israel "track down an Islamic
militant terror squad" in Gaza. Palestinian security forces also
worked together with Israelis in Hebron to try to stem violent
clashes.
</P>
<P>
Burns said "that is quite positive" as security cooperation
between the two sides re-emerged, and the next step was to
reinvigorate the peace negotiations and to move them forward.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has put ideas this week before the Israeli
prime minister and the Palestinian delegation, and we hope that
they'll all reflect very seriously upon those ideas," Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here said even if the United States succeeds in
bringing the two sides back to the table, there are no guarantees
the talks will not collapse again.
</P>
<P>
No one could be sure the Israelis would not take one more
preempting move before final status negotiations in the zero-sum
game, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They are now assured of Palestinian commitment to renouncing
terrorism, but they themselves made no signal that they would
abide by peace agreements between the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The recent violent clashes erupted on the West Bank as a result
of Israel's decision to build Jewish homes in traditionally Arab
east Jerusalem. The clashes led to several Palestinians killed by
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Burns admitted the peace negotiations between the Palestinians
and Israelis "are at an impasse."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. objective is to revive them. And to do that, we've
suggested some substantive ideas that might bridge the gap between
the Palestinians and the Israelis," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
